[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens in Skamania County, Washington experienced a catastrophic explosive eruption which had a volcanic explosivity index of 5.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] It was the first to occur in the contiguous United States since the much smaller 1915 eruption of Lassen Peak in California.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The main eruption was preceded by a series of volcanic explosions, pyroclastic flows, and phreatic blasts beginning in March 1980.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] It has often been considered the most disastrous volcanic event in U.S. history.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The eruption was preceded by a series of earthquakes and steam-venting episodes caused by an injection of magma at shallow depth below the volcano that created a large bulge and a fracture system on the mountain's north slope.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] An earthquake at 8:32:11 am PDT (UTC−7) on May 18, 1980, caused the entire weakened north face to slide away, a sector collapse which was the largest subaerial landslide in recorded history.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This allowed the partly molten rock, rich in high-pressure gas and steam, to suddenly explode northward toward Spirit Lake in a hot mix of lava and pulverized rock, overtaking the landslide.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] An eruption column rose 80,000 feet (24 km; 15 mi) into the atmosphere and deposited ash in 11 U.S. states and various Canadian provinces.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] At the same time, snow, ice, and several entire glaciers on the volcano melted, forming a series of large lahars (volcanic mudslides) that reached as far as the Columbia River, nearly 50 miles (80 km; 260,000 ft) to the southwest.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Less severe outbursts continued into the next day, only to be followed by other large, but not as destructive, eruptions later that year.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The thermal energy released during the eruption was equal to 26 megatons of TNT.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] About 57 people were killed, including innkeeper and World War I veteran Harry R.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Truman, photographers Reid Blackburn and Robert Landsburg, and volcanologist David A.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Hundreds of square miles were reduced to wasteland, causing over $1 billion in damage (equivalent to $3.5 billion in 2024).
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Thousands of animals were killed, and Mount St.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens was left with a crater on its north side.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] At the time of the eruption, the summit of the volcano was owned by the Burlington Northern Railroad, but the United States Forest Service acquired the land from the railroad after the eruption.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The area was later preserved in the Mount St.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens National Volcanic Monument and the State of Washington recognized the month of May as "Volcano Awareness Month".
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens and within the region to discuss the eruption and safety concerns, and to commemorate lives lost during the disaster.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens remained dormant from its last period of activity in the 1840s and 1850s until March 1980.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Several small earthquakes, beginning on March 15, indicated that magma might have begun moving below the volcano.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] On March 20, at 3:45 pm Pacific Standard Time, a shallow 4.2-magnitude earthquake, centered below the volcano's north flank, signaled the volcano's return from 123 years of hibernation.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] A gradually building earthquake swarm saturated area seismographs and started to climax at about noon on March 25, reaching peak levels in the next two days, including an earthquake registering 5.1 on the Richter scale among a total of 174 shocks of magnitude 2.6 or greater.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Shocks of magnitude 3.2 or greater occurred at a slightly increasing rate during April and May, with five earthquakes of magnitude 4 or above per day in early April, and eight per day the week before May 18.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Initially, no direct sign of eruption was seen, but small earthquake-induced avalanches of snow and ice were reported from aerial observations.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] At 12:36 pm on March 27, phreatic eruptions (explosions of steam caused by magma suddenly heating groundwater) ejected and smashed rock from within the old summit crater, excavating a new crater 250 feet (75 m) wide, and sending an ash column about 7,000 feet (2.1 km) into the air.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] By this date, a 16,000-foot-long (4.9 km) eastward-trending fracture system had also developed across the summit area.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This was followed by more earthquake swarms and a series of steam explosions that sent ash 10,000 to 11,000 feet (3,000 to 3,400 m) above their vent.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Most of this ash fell between 3 and 12 mi (5 and 19 km) from its vent, but some was carried 150 mi (240 km) south to Bend, Oregon, or 285 mi (460 km) east to Spokane, Washington.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] A second, new crater and a blue flame were observed on March 29.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The flame was visibly emitted from both craters and was probably created by burning gases.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Static electricity generated from ash clouds rolling down the volcano sent out lightning bolts that were up to 2 mi (3 km) long.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Ninety-three separate outbursts were reported on March 30, and increasingly strong harmonic tremors were first detected on April 1, alarming geologists and prompting Governor Dixy Lee Ray to declare a state of emergency on April 3.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Governor Ray issued an executive order on April 30 creating a "red zone" around the volcano; anyone caught in this zone without a pass faced a $500 fine (equivalent to $2,000 in 2025) or six months in jail.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This precluded many cabin owners from visiting their property.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] A USGS (United States Geological Survey) team determined in the last week of April that a 1.5 mi-diameter (2.4 km) section of St.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens' north face was displaced outward by at least 270 ft (82 m).
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] For the rest of April and early May, this bulge grew by 5 to 6 ft (1.5 to 1.8 m) per day, and by mid-May, it extended more than 400 ft (120 m) north.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] As the bulge moved northward, the summit area behind it progressively sank, forming a complex, down-dropped block called a graben.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Geologists announced on April 30 that sliding of the bulge area was the greatest immediate danger and that such a landslide might spark an eruption.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] These changes in the volcano's shape were related to the overall deformation that increased the volume of the volcano by 0.03 mi3 (0.13 km3) by mid-May.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This volume increase presumably corresponded to the volume of magma that pushed into the volcano and deformed its surface.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Because the intruding magma remained below ground and was not directly visible, it was called a cryptodome, in contrast to a true lava dome exposed at the surface.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Volcanologist Barry Voight was contacted by Rocky Crandell, a USGS employee working in the Vancouver office near the mountain.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Crandell sought Voight's expertise in landslides, hoping Voight would opine on the growing bulge.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] In his reporting to Crandell and his associates, Voight, who observed the mountain from April 11-19, said that the bulge could fail and collapse the volcano's entire north sector.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] He suggested they begin monitoring the rate of movement of the bulge, worried that the collapse could trigger an eruption.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] He also advised hiring a local surveyor to take measurements, offending several of the geologists.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Shortly after, Voight left the mountain and returned to teaching classes at Pennsylvania State University.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] On May 1, he sent his full report to the USGS, summarizing his predictions, predicting the failure of the bulge and the collapse of the mountain's north side followed by a violent eruption that would require an extensive evacuation zone.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] On May 7, eruptions similar to those in March and April resumed, and over the following days, the bulge approached its maximum size.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] All activity had been confined to the 350-year-old summit dome and did not involve any new magma.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] About 10,000 earthquakes were recorded before the May 18 event, with most concentrated in a small zone less than 1.6 mi (2.6 km) directly below the bulge.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Visible eruptions ceased on May 16, reducing public interest and consequently the number of spectators in the area.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Mounting public pressure then forced officials to allow 50 carloads of property owners to enter the danger zone on Saturday, May 17, to gather whatever property they could carry.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Another trip was scheduled for 10 am the next day, a Sunday, when more than three hundred loggers who would normally be working in the area were not present.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] By the time of the climactic eruption, dacite magma intruding into the volcano had forced the north flank outward nearly 500 ft (150 m) and heated the volcano's groundwater system, causing many steam-driven explosions (phreatic eruptions).
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens' activity did not show any change from the pattern of the preceding month.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The rates of bulge movement and sulfur dioxide emission, and ground temperature readings did not reveal any changes indicating a catastrophic eruption.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Johnston was on duty at an observation post around 6 mi (10 km) north of the volcano.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] At 6:00 am Johnston's measurements did not indicate any unusual activity.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] At 8:32 am, a magnitude 5.1 earthquake centered directly below the north slope triggered that part of the volcano to slide, approximately 7–20 seconds after the shock, followed a few seconds later by the main volcanic blast.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The sector collapse, the largest subaerial landslide in recorded history, traveled at 110 to 155 mph (180 to 250 km/h; 50 to 70 m/s) and moved across Spirit Lake's west arm.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Part of it hit a 1,150 ft-high (350 m) ridge about 6 mi (10 km) north.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Some of the slide spilled over the ridge, but most of it moved 13 mi (21 km) down the North Fork Toutle River, filling its valley up to 600 feet (180 m) deep with avalanche debris.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] An area of about 24 mi2 (62 km2) was covered, and the total volume of the deposit was about 0.7 mi3 (2.9 km3).
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Rosenquist, his party, and his photographs survived because the blast was deflected by local topography 1 mi (1.6 km) short of his location.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens' former north side became a rubble deposit 17 mi (27 km) long, averaging 150 ft (46 m) thick; the slide was thickest at 1 mi (1.6 km) below Spirit Lake and thinnest at its western margin.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The landslide temporarily displaced the waters of Spirit Lake to the ridge north of the lake, in a giant wave about 600 ft (180 m) high.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This, in turn, created a 295 ft (90 m) avalanche of debris consisting of the returning waters and thousands of uprooted trees and stumps.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Some of these remained intact with roots, but most had been sheared off at the stump seconds earlier by the blast of superheated volcanic gas and ash that had immediately followed and overtaken the initial landslide.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The debris was transported along with the water as it returned to its basin, raising the surface level of Spirit Lake by about 200 ft (61 m).
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Four decades after the eruption, floating log mats persist on Spirit Lake and nearby St.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens Lake, changing position with the wind.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The rest of the trees, especially those that were not completely detached from their roots, were turned upright by their own weight and became waterlogged, sinking into the muddy sediments at the bottom where they are in the process of becoming petrified in the anaerobic and mineral-rich waters.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This provides insight into other sites with a similar fossil record.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The landslide exposed the dacite magma in Mount St.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens' neck to much lower pressure, causing the gas-charged, partially molten rock and high-pressure steam above it to explode a few seconds after the landslide started.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Explosions burst through the trailing part of the landslide, blasting rock debris northward.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The resulting blast directed the pyroclastic flow laterally.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] It consisted of very hot volcanic gases, ash, and pumice formed from new lava, as well as pulverized old rock, which hugged the ground.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Initially moving about 220 mph (350 km/h), the blast quickly accelerated to around 670 mph (1,080 km/h), and it may have briefly passed the speed of sound.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Pyroclastic flow material passed over the moving avalanche and spread outward, devastating a fan-shaped area 23 miles across by 19 miles long (37 km by 31 km).
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] In total, about 230 sq mi (600 km2) of forest were knocked down, and extreme heat killed trees miles beyond the blow-down zone.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] At its vent, the lateral blast probably did not last longer than about thirty seconds, but the northward-radiating and expanding blast cloud continued for about another minute.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This so-called "quiet zone" extended radially a few tens of miles from the volcano and was created by the complex response of the eruption's sound waves to differences in temperature and air motion of the atmospheric layers, and to a lesser extent, local topography.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Later studies indicated that one-third of the 0.045 mi3 (0.19 km3) of material in the flow was new lava, and the rest was fragmented, older rock.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The huge ensuing ash cloud sent skyward from St.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens' northern foot was visible throughout the quiet zone.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The near-supersonic lateral blast, loaded with volcanic debris, caused devastation as far as 19 mi (31 km) from the volcano.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Channelized blast zone, an intermediate zone, extended out to distances as far as 19 mi (31 km) from the volcano, an area in which the flow flattened everything in its path and was channeled to some extent by topography.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] In this zone, the forces and direction of the blast are strikingly demonstrated by the parallel alignment of toppled large trees, broken off at the base of the trunk as if they were blades of grass mown by a scythe.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This zone was also known as the "tree-down zone".
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Channeling and deflection of the blast caused strikingly varied local effects that still remained conspicuous after some decades.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Where the blast struck open land directly, it scoured it, breaking trees off short and stripping vegetation and even topsoil, thereby delaying revegetation for many years.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Where the blast was deflected so as to pass overhead by several metres, it left the topsoil and the seeds it contained, permitting faster revegetation with scrub and herbaceous plants, and later with saplings.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Trees in the path of such higher-level blasts were broken off wholesale at various heights, whereas nearby stands in more sheltered positions recovered comparatively rapidly without conspicuous long-term harm.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Seared zone, also called the "standing dead" zone, the outermost fringe of the impacted area, is a zone in which trees remained standing, but were singed brown by the hot gases of the blast.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] By the time this pyroclastic flow hit its first human victims, it was still as hot as 680 °F (360 °C) and filled with suffocating gas and flying debris.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Most of the 57 people known to have died in that day's eruption succumbed to asphyxiation, while several died from burns.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] He was able to protect his film with his body, and the surviving photos provided geologists with valuable documentation of the historic eruption.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Another eruption victim, amateur radio operator Gerry Martin, located near the Coldwater peak and farther north of Johnston's position 46°17′59.7″N 122°12′55″W﻿ / ﻿46.299917°N 122.21528°W﻿ / 46.299917; -122.21528, reported his sighting of the eruption enveloping the Coldwater II observation post.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] As the blast overwhelmed Johnston's post, Martin declared solemnly: "Gentlemen, the camper and car that's sitting over to the south of me is covered.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] It's going to hit me, too." before his radio went silent.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Subsequent outpourings of pyroclastic material from the breach left by the landslide consisted mainly of new magmatic debris rather than fragments of pre-existing volcanic rocks.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The resulting deposits formed a fan-like pattern of overlapping sheets, tongues, and lobes.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] At least 17 separate pyroclastic flows occurred during the May 18 eruption, and their aggregate volume was about 0.05 mi3 (0.21 km3).
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The flow deposits were still at about 570 to 790 °F (300 to 420 °C) two weeks after they erupted.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Secondary steam-blast eruptions fed by this heat created pits on the northern margin of the pyroclastic-flow deposits, at the south shore of Spirit Lake, and along the upper part of the North Fork Toutle River.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] These steam-blast explosions continued sporadically for weeks or months after the emplacement of pyroclastic flows, and at least one occurred a year later, on May 16, 1981.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] As the avalanche and initial pyroclastic flow were still advancing, a huge ash column grew to a height of 12 mi (19 km) above the expanding crater in less than ten minutes and spread tephra into the stratosphere for ten straight hours.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Near the volcano, the swirling ash particles in the atmosphere generated lightning, which in turn started many forest fires.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] During this time, parts of the mushroom-shaped ash-cloud column collapsed, and fell back upon the earth.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This fallout, mixed with magma, mud, and steam, sent additional pyroclastic flows speeding down St.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Later, slower flows came directly from the new north-facing crater and consisted of glowing pumice bombs and very hot pumiceous ash.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Some of these hot flows covered ice or water, which flashed to steam, creating craters up to 65 ft (20 m) in diameter and sending ash as much as 6,500 ft (2,000 m) into the air.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Strong, high-altitude wind carried much of this material east-northeasterly from the volcano at an average speed around 60 miles per hour (100 km/h).
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] By 9:45 am, it had reached Yakima, Washington, 90 mi (140 km) away, and by 11:45 it was over Spokane, Washington.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] A total of 4 to 5 in (100 to 130 mm) of ash fell on Yakima, and areas as far east as Spokane were plunged into darkness by noon, where visibility was reduced to 10 ft (3 m) and 0.5 in (13 mm) of ash fell.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens' ash fell in the western part of Yellowstone National Park by 10:15 pm, and was seen on the ground in Denver the next day.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] In time, ash fall from this eruption was reported as far away as Minnesota and Oklahoma, and some of the ash drifted around the globe within about two weeks.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] During the nine hours of vigorous eruptive activity, about 540,000,000 tons (540×10^6 short tons or 490×10^6 t) of ash fell over an area of more than 22,000 mi2 (57,000 km2).
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The total volume of the ash before its compaction by rainfall was about 0.3 mi3 (1.3 km3).
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The volume of the uncompacted ash is equivalent to about 0.05 mi3 (0.21 km3) of solid rock, or about 7% of the amount of material that slid off in the debris avalanche.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] By 5:30 pm on May 18, the vertical ash column declined in stature, but less severe outbursts continued through the next several days.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Generally, given that the way airborne ash is deposited after an eruption is strongly influenced by the meteorological conditions, a certain variation of the ash type will occur, as a function of distance to the volcano or time elapsed from eruption.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens is no exception, hence the ash properties have large variations.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The bulk chemical composition of the ash has been found to be about 65% silicon dioxide, 18% aluminum oxide, 5% ferric oxide, 4% each calcium oxide and sodium oxide, and 2% magnesium oxide.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Trace elements were also detected, their concentrations varying as 0.05–0.09% chlorine, 0.02–0.03% fluorine, and 0.09–0.3% sulfur.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The index of refraction, a measure used in physics to describe how light propagates through a particular substance, is an important property of volcanic ash.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This number is *complex*, having both *real* and *imaginary* parts, the real part indicating how light disperses and the imaginary part indicating how light is absorbed by the substance.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The silicate particles are known to have a real index of refraction ranging between 1.5 and 1.6 for visible light.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] However, a spectrum of colors is associated with samples of volcanic ash, from very light to dark gray.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This makes for variations in the measured imaginary refractive index under visible light.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] For example, when comparing the imaginary part of the refractive index *k* of stratospheric ash from 9.3 and 11.2 mi (15 and 18 km) from the volcano, they have similar values around 700 nm (around 0.009), while they differ significantly around 300 nm.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Here, the 11.2 mi (18 km) sample (*k* was found to be around 0.009) was much more absorbent than the 9.3 mi (15 km) sample (*k* was found to be around 0.002).
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The hot, exploding material also broke apart and melted nearly all of the mountain's glaciers, along with most of the overlying snow.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens eruptions, this created huge lahars (volcanic mudflows) and muddy floods that affected three of the four stream drainage systems on the mountain, and which started to move as early as 8:50 am.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Lahars travelled as fast as 90 mph (140 km/h) while still high on the volcano, but progressively slowed to about 3 mph (4.8 km/h) on the flatter and wider parts of rivers.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Mudflows from the southern and eastern flanks had the consistency of wet concrete as they raced down Muddy River, Pine Creek, and Smith Creek to their confluence at the Lewis River.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Bridges were taken out at the mouth of Pine Creek and the head of Swift Reservoir, which rose 2.6 ft (0.79 m) by noon to accommodate the nearly 18,000,000 yd3 (14,000,000 m3) of additional water, mud, and debris.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Glacier and snowmelt mixed with tephra on the volcano's northeast slope to create much larger lahars.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] These mudflows traveled down the north and south forks of the Toutle River and joined at the confluence of the Toutle forks and the Cowlitz River near Castle Rock, Washington, at 1:00 pm.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Ninety minutes after the eruption, the first mudflow had moved 27 mi (43 km) upstream, where observers at Weyerhaeuser's Camp Baker saw a 12 ft-high (4 m) wall of muddy water and debris pass.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Near the confluence of the Toutle's north and south forks at Silver Lake, a record flood stage of 23.5 ft (7.2 m) was recorded.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] A large but slower-moving mudflow with a mortar-like consistency was mobilized in early afternoon at the head of the Toutle River north fork.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] By 2:30 pm the massive mudflow had destroyed Camp Baker, and in the following hours, seven bridges were carried away.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Part of the flow backed up for 2.5 mi (4.0 km) soon after entering the Cowlitz River, but most continued downstream.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] After traveling 17 mi (27 km) further, an estimated 3,900,000 yd3 (3,000,000 m3) of material were injected into the Columbia River, reducing the river's depth by 25 ft (8 m) for a 4 mi (6 km) stretch.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The resulting 13 ft (4.0 m) river depth temporarily closed the busy channel to ocean-going freighters, costing Portland, Oregon, an estimated $5 million (equivalent to $15.9 million 2024).
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Ultimately, more than 65×10^6 yd3 (50×10^6 m3; 1.8×10^9 ft3) of sediment were dumped along the lower Cowlitz and Columbia Rivers.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The May 18, 1980, event was the most deadly and economically destructive volcanic eruption in the history of the contiguous United States.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] About 57 people were killed directly from the blast, and 200 houses, 47 bridges, 15 mi (24 km) of railways, and 185 mi (298 km) of highway were destroyed; two people were killed indirectly in accidents that resulted from poor visibility, and two more suffered fatal heart attacks from shoveling ash.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] President Jimmy Carter surveyed the damage, and said it looked more desolate than a moonscape.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] A film crew was dropped by helicopter on Mount St.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens on May 23 to document the destruction, but they quickly became lost, which the crew attributed to “magnetism in the ash and our contour maps made meaningless on the altered slopes”.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] A second eruption occurred the next day (see below), but the crew survived and were rescued two days after that.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The eruption ejected more than 1 mi3 (4.2 km3) of material.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] A quarter of that volume was fresh lava in the form of ash, pumice, and volcanic bombs, while the rest was fragmented, older rock.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The removal of the north side of the mountain (13% of the cone's volume) reduced Mount St.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens' height by about 1,300 ft (400 m) and left a crater 1 to 2 mi (1.6 to 3.2 km) wide and 2,100 ft (640 m) deep with its north end open in a huge breach.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] More than 4,000,000,000 board feet (9,400,000 m3) of timber were damaged or destroyed, mainly by the lateral blast.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] At least 25% of the destroyed timber was salvaged after September 1980.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Downwind of the volcano, in areas of thick ash accumulation, many agricultural crops, such as wheat, apples, potatoes, and alfalfa, were destroyed.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] As many as 1,500 elk and 5,000 deer were killed, and an estimated twelve million Chinook and Coho salmon fingerlings died when their hatcheries were destroyed.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Another estimated 40,000 young salmon were killed when they swam through turbine blades of hydroelectric generators after reservoir levels were lowered along the Lewis River to accommodate possible mudflows and flood waters.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens released 24 megatons TNT of thermal energy, seven of which were a direct result of the blast.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This is equivalent to 1,600 times the size of the atomic bomb dropped on Hiroshima.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] In 2024, a study was conducted that provided an explanation for the observed phenomenon of an increase in the duration of the Lamb waves compared to the expected.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The death toll most commonly cited is 57, although two points of uncertainty remain.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The first point regards two officially listed victims, Paul Hiatt and Dale Thayer.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] They were reported missing after the explosion.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] In the aftermath, investigators were able to locate individuals named Paul Hiatt and Dale Thayer who were alive and well.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] However, they were unable to determine who reported Hiatt missing, and the person who was listed as reporting Thayer missing claimed she was not the one who had done so.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Since the investigators could not thus verify that they were the same Hiatt and Thayer who were reported missing, the names remain listed among the presumed dead.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The second point regards three missing people who are not officially listed as victims: Robert Ruffle, Steven Whitsett, and Mark Melanson.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Cowlitz County Emergency Services Management lists them as "Possibly Missing — Not on [the official] List".
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] According to Melanson's brother, in October 1983, Cowlitz County officials told his family that Melanson "is believed [...] a victim of the May 18, 1980, eruption" and that after years of searching, the family eventually decided "he's buried in the ash".
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Taking these two points of uncertainty into consideration, the direct death toll could be as low as 55 or as high as 60.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] When combined with the four indirect victims (two dying from vehicle accidents due to poor visibility, and two dying from heart attacks triggered by shovelling ash) those numbers range from 59 to 64.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] A year and a half after the eruption, the bodies of two young women, Marsha Anne Weatter and Katherine Jean Allen, 18 and 20 years old respectively, were discovered.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] They were believed to have been murdered six weeks before the eruption, rather than being killed by the events.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Backpacks belonging to them had been found in July 1980, but a layer of ash deposited by the eruption may have hidden the bodies, also preventing animals disturbing the remains.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] An autopsy showed they had each been shot once.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The murders of Weatter and Allen were later linked to serial killer Martin Lee Sanders.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The ash fall created some temporary major problems with transportation, sewage disposal, and water treatment systems.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Visibility was greatly decreased during the ash fall, closing many highways and roads.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Interstate 90 from Seattle to Spokane was closed for a week and a half.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Air travel was disrupted for between a few days and two weeks, as several airports in eastern Washington shut down because of ash accumulation and poor visibility.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Over a thousand commercial flights were cancelled following airport closures.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Fine-grained, gritty ash caused substantial problems for internal combustion engines and other mechanical and electrical equipment.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The ash contaminated oil systems, clogged air filters, and scratched moving surfaces.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Fine ash caused short circuits in electrical transformers, which in turn caused power blackouts.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Removing and disposing of the ash was a monumental task for some Eastern Washington communities.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] State and federal agencies estimated that over 2,400,000 yd3 (1,800,000 m3) of ash, equivalent to about 900,000 tons in weight, were removed from highways and airports in Washington.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The ash removal cost $2.2 million and took ten weeks in Yakima.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The need to remove ash quickly from transport routes and civil works dictated the selection of some disposal sites.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Some cities used old quarries and existing sanitary landfills; others created dump sites wherever expedient.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] To minimize wind reworking of ash dumps, the surfaces of some disposal sites were covered with topsoil and seeded with grass.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] In Portland, the mayor eventually threatened businesses with fines if they failed to remove the ash from their parking lots.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] A refined estimate of $1.1 billion ($3.5 billion in 2024) was determined in a study by the International Trade Commission at the request of the U.S.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] A supplemental appropriation of $951 million for disaster relief was voted by Congress, of which the largest share went to the Small Business Administration, the U.S.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Army Corps of Engineers, and the Federal Emergency Management Agency.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Also, indirect and intangible costs of the eruption were incurred.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Unemployment in the immediate region of Mount St.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens rose 10-fold in the weeks immediately following the eruption, and then returned to near-normal levels once timber-salvaging and ash-cleanup operations were underway.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Only a small percentage of residents left the region because of lost jobs owing to the eruption.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Several months after May 18, a few residents reported suffering stress and emotional problems, though they had coped successfully during the crisis.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Counties in the region requested funding for mental-health programs to assist such people.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Initial public reaction to the May 18 eruption dealt a nearly crippling blow to tourism, an important industry in Washington.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Not only was tourism down in the Mount St.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens–Gifford Pinchot National Forest area, but conventions, meetings and social gatherings also were cancelled or postponed at cities and resorts elsewhere in Washington and neighboring Oregon not affected by the eruption.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The adverse effect on tourism and conventioneering, however, proved only temporary.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens, perhaps because of its reawakening, has regained its appeal for tourists.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Forest Service and the State of Washington opened visitor centers and provided access for people to view the volcano's devastation.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens produced an additional five explosive eruptions between May and October 1980.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Through early 1990, at least 21 periods of eruptive activity occurred.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The volcano remains active, with smaller, dome-building eruptions continuing into 2008.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] An eruption occurred on May 25, 1980, at 2:30am that sent an ash column 9 mi (48,000 ft; 14 km) into the atmosphere.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The eruption was preceded by a sudden increase in earthquake activity, and occurred during a rainstorm.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Erratic wind from the storm carried ash from the eruption to the south and west, lightly dusting large parts of western Washington and Oregon.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Pyroclastic flows exited the northern breach and covered avalanche debris, lahars, and other pyroclastic flows deposited by the May 18 eruption.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] At 7:05 pm on June 12, a plume of ash billowed 2.5 mi (4.0 km) above the volcano.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] At 9:09 pm, a much stronger explosion sent an ash column about 10 mi (16 km) skyward.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This event caused the Portland area, previously spared by wind direction, to be thinly coated with ash in the middle of the annual Rose Festival.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] A dacite dome then oozed into existence on the crater floor, growing to a height of 200 ft (61 m) and a width of 1,200 ft (370 m) within a week.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] A series of large explosions on July 22 broke more than a month of relative quiet.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The July eruptive episode was preceded by several days of measurable expansion of the summit area, heightened earthquake activity, and changed emission rates of sulfur dioxide and carbon dioxide.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The first hit at 5:14 pm as an ash column shot 10 mi (16 km) and was followed by a faster blast at 6:25 pm that pushed the ash column above its previous maximum height in just 7.5 minutes.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The final explosion started at 7:01 pm, and continued over two hours.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] When the relatively small amount of ash settled over eastern Washington, the dome built in June was gone.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Seismic activity and gas emission steadily increased in early August, and on August 7 at 4:26 pm an ash cloud slowly expanded 8 mi (13 km) into the sky.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Small pyroclastic flows came through the northern breach and a weaker outpouring of ash rose from the crater.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This continued until 10:32 pm, when a second large blast sent ash high into the air, proceeding due north.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] A second dacite dome filled this vent a few days later.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Two months of repose were ended by an eruption lasting from October 16 to 18.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This event obliterated the second dome, sent ash ten miles in the air, and created small, red-hot pyroclastic flows.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] A third dome began to form within thirty minutes after the final explosion on October 18, and within a few days it was about 900 ft (270 m) wide and 130 ft (40 m) high.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] In spite of the dome growth next to it, a new glacier formed rapidly inside the crater.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] All of the post-1980 eruptions were quiet dome-building events, beginning with the December 27, 1980, to January 3, 1981, episode.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] By 1987 the third dome had grown to be more than 3,000 ft (910 m) wide and 800 ft (240 m) high.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Further eruptions occurred over a few months between 1989 and 1991.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The 2004–2008 volcanic activity of Mount St.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens has been documented as a continuous eruption with a gradual extrusion of magma at the Mount St.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Starting in October 2004, a gradual building of a new lava dome happened.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The new dome did not rise above the crater created by the 1980 eruption.
[src:geology/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This activity lasted until January 2008.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] In geology, **3D fold evolution** is the study of the full three dimensional structure of a fold as it changes in time.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] A fold is a common three-dimensional geological structure that is associated with strain deformation under stress.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Fold evolution in three dimensions can be broadly divided into two stages, namely fold growth and fold linkage.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] The evolution depends on fold kinematics, Fold mechanism, as well as a reporting of the history behind folds and relationships by which fold age is understood.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] There are several ways to reconstruct the evolution progress of folds, notably by using depositional evidence, geomorphological evidence and balanced restoration.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Under compressional stress, folds grow in all three dimensions, including vertical fold amplification and lateral fold propagation, both along fold crest and perpendicular to fold crests.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Three-dimensional fold growth can be observed in areas like the Zagros Mountains in Iraq and Iran as well as Wheeler Ridge in California, United States.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] The vertical dimension of a fold can be described as an amplitude.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] The horizontal dimension of a fold can by described by wavelength and hinge line of a fold.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] As a fold grows in three-dimension, amplitude, wavelength and the length of the hinge line will increase.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Sheath folds form in areas where rocks react differently to simple shear, due to variations in competence across layers.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] The hinge line is severely bent in sheath fold.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Under force, rock strata buckle occurs by one of two kinematic processes, either by hinge migration or by limb rotation.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] A fold hinge can migrate when strata are folded by hinge migration but the hinge is fixed when strata are folded by limb rotation.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] At least one of the fold hinges in the whole fold structure is mobile during three dimensional fold growth.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] For example, indicated by kinematic models, the structure of a fault-propagation folds should contain three anticlines/synclines with migrating hinges and 1 anticline with fixed hinge limb rotation.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Hinge migration can be distinguished from limb rotation by several structural and geomorphological features.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Growth strata, also known as syntectonic strata, are sedimentary layers that are deposited at the same time as folding.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] These layers are characterized by decreasing thickness of strata towards crest of an anticline(fig 1).
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] They exist in various geometric patterns.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] The variation in geometric patterns can be attributed to fold kinematics, rate of uplift and sedimentation rate.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] A knickpoint is a morphological term for a section of a present or abandoned river valley that shows an abrupt change in slope, and can be attributed to differential erosion or structural deformation.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] They are usually associated with waterfalls and lakes.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] For the definition of wind gaps, please see subsection #streams deflected around the nose of fold.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Folds that may experience prolonged 3D growth can be divided into two groups according to their causes, namely detachment fold and forced fold.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] They are mainly differentiated by the presence of major fault control on fold structure in forced folds, and the absence of it in detachment folds.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Fold causes that do not contribute to significant fold growth in all three dimensions, such as en-echelon folds, drag folds and rollover anticline are not in these groups.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Understanding the evolution of folds is important because it helps petroleum geologists to gain a better understanding on the distribution of structural traps of hydrocarbon.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] In a setting in which overlapping strata acquires contrasting competency, a decollement (interface between paper and table) is usually found along strata in competent rock unit (such as sandstone) or along the interface of competent and incompetent rock unit (such as an evaporite).
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] A fold acquires higher amplitude, longer wavelength and broader width when rock strata above the decollement are subjected to shortening stress parallel to, or at a low angle to the strata.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Apart from stress parameters, contrast of competency across strata and variation of displacement along the decollement are the main factors contributing to fold geometry and three dimensional growth pattern.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Two common types of forced folds are, namely, fault-bend fold and fault-propagation fold.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Folding occurs above the hanging wall of a fold ramp in a fault-bend fold, while folding occurs above the truncation of a thrust fault(fault tip) in a fault-propagation fold.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] They are usually highly asymmetric with one side of the limb much steeper than the other side.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Shortening stress is usually at a high angle to the strata and is concentrated along the slipping plane and in the hanging wall of the thrust fault.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] The fold acquires higher amplitude, longer wavelength and broader width as rock slips along the fault plane of the underlying coeval thrust fault, casting major influence on the three dimensional growth of the fold.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Therefore, forced folds are controlled by the fault structure in the basement rocks along planar or listric fault surfaces.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] The amount of fault displacement would control the amplitude of a fold, the lateral growth of fault would implies lateral growth of fold and fault linkage implies fold linkage on the surface.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] When compared to detachment folds, contrasting competency across strata is not as pronounced and the tectonic environments that they are found in are often more diverse.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] A detachment fold can evolve into a forced fold when shortening stress exceeds the maximum strength of rock, and as a result the decollement may propagate upwards towards the anticlinal core and fault the detachment fold.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] The resultant structure poses characteristics of both detachment fold and fault propagation fold.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] An exemplar structure of this kind can be found in Mississippi Fan fold belt in Gulf of Mexico.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Modelling of the kinematic evolution of folds in cross-sectional view is usually based on one of the following schemes: balanced restoration, forward kinematic modelling or a combination of the two.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Section restoration in all three dimension can only be done by highly specialized software and is mainly used for studies in hydrocarbon.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Alternatively, geomorphological evidences, especially drainage features, can be used to determine the lateral propagation direction of fold growth.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Drainage density (=total river length/area of drainage basin) and degree of surface dissection decreases along with propagation direction of a fold.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Higher drainage density and greater degree of surface dissection in a particular part of a fold segment corresponds to the higher maturity of that part, which can be inferred as that that part has been subjected to erosion for a longer time period after uplift.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Hence, it experienced uplift relative earlier than other parts of the fold.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Mathematical analysis of the maturity of drainage which take into the account of stream length and stream order can also be used to establish the relative ages of different drainage basins.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Older sections of a fold experience more erosion and therefore have a different soil profile compared to their younger counterparts.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Furthermore, carbon-14 or uranium-series dating of soil materials would set time constraint on certain parts of the fold and therefore helps fixing the rate of lateral fold growth.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Therefore, the progressive change in soil profile is more of a secondary evidence of lateral fold growth.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Structural elevation along fold crest should decrease along the growth direction of a fold because the older part of a fold experiences more uplift than their younger counterpart.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] However, this can be strongly misleading in active erosional environment where erosion rather than uplift due to fold growth is the dominant shaping force of the landscape and as a result can only be used as secondary evidence of fold growth.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] An asymmetric forked drainage pattern forms during lateral growth of a fold.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] The direction along which drainage channels 'bend away' from the fold crest is the direction of lateral fold growth(fig.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Imagine the following situation: at an early stage of folding and near the fold tip, river flows approximately along the fold crests towards the end of a fold as river tends to flow down the slope of maximum gradient.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] As folding continues, that point is no longer located at the fold tip as the fold grows laterally.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] As the point is uplifted to a higher elevation, the slope of maximum gradient is no longer along the fold crest, but becomes the distance from fold hinge towards the other end of fold limb, which is approximately perpendicular to the original orientation.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] As a result, the new generation of river flows perpendicular to the fold crest along the fold limbs.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Because of strong river erosion in the upper course, some of the drainage channels of the earlier stage are deeply incised into bedrock and therefore river continues to flow along these upper parts of old channels that do not follow the maximum slope gradient.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] This criterion is a strong evidence for lateral fold growth.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Streams are deflected as they meet uplifted rocks and flow along the boundary of the fold, which is parallel or sub-parallel to fold axis and the curvature of the deflected stream convex towards the direction of lateral fold growth along fold crest.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] There are two possible scenarios when the path of a stream is blocked by an uplifted block of rock.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] First scenario: the stream poses stream power that is high enough to cut through the uplifted rocks, so that the river course will not be significantly altered.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] A channel is opened in the uplifted rocks due to erosion, a landform known as water gap.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] It continues to flow until the rock is further uplifted and the river no longer has enough erosive power to cut through it, leading to the second scenario.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Second scenario: the stream does not have enough erosive power to cut through the rocks, so it deflected to flow along the boundary of the uplifted block as aforementioned.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] The abandoned river channel is known as wind gap.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Elevation of wind gaps decreases along the growth direction of fold and curvature of curved wind gaps convex towards the growth direction of the fold.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Multiple wind gaps can be formed from a single river if there is continuous lateral fold growth and the river keeps being deflected, by abandoning its earlier channel and forming a new one around the outside of the developing fold.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] In a topographic profile along fold crest, wind gaps appears as deep, narrow v-shaped valley.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] The incision depth of a wind gap correspond to the period of active river erosion before the channel was abandoned, i.e. the duration of its state of being a river or water gap.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Therefore, the elevation of wind gaps must always decrease along the direction of lateral fold growth along fold crest, which is one of the strongest, although not decisive, evidence of the characteristics of fold growth.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] As former deflected streams, some of the wind gaps may show curvature that convex towards the direction of lateral fold growth.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] In a Digital Elevation Model(DEM), the longitudinal profile of a wind gap shows a convex-upwards trend and that of a water gap shows a concave-upwards or linear trend.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Located at southern California, Wheeler Ridge anticline is an east–west trending fault-bend fold, and is part of Pleito-Wheeler Ridge thrust fault system.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Structural deformation in the area has been active since late Pleistocene, resulting in significant three-dimensional fold growth.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] The eastern end of the anticline has been experiencing fold growth towards the east-southeast.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Firstly, the structural elevation of eastern Wheeler Ridge decreases from the west to east, suggesting that the eastern part of the examined section is uplifted and exposed to erosion at a later time than the western part of the examined section.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Second, the main flowing river channels show a curvature that bends towards the east-southeast.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] The curvature seems to a result of gradual uplift of rocks towards the east-southeast and shows resemblance to the patterns of deflected streams during lateral fold growth.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Under this assumption, this evidence supports the growth of fold towards the east-southeast.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Third, the abandonment of old river channels (formation of wind gap) can be seen in a topographic profile across ridge crest.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] It seems that the river originally flowing in the wind gap was deflected due to uplifting and flow along water gap 1 instead.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Therefore, there is a strong evidence supporting that fold grows laterally towards east-southeast.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Forth, soil analysis indicates a high level of soil development at the western part of the examined section indicates, and the level of soil development gradually decreases towards the east.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] It is suggested that western part of the examined area is of an older age comparing to the eastern part, and therefore the fold grows from west to east.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] In an area affected by regional stress, most of the faults and folds are aligned along strike.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] In forced folds, linkage of folds is strongly associated with linkage of the underlying faults.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Growth and displacement of faults are affected by not only the far-field stress of the region but also the position of faults relative to each other.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Conversely, the faults that are located in stress shadow are relaxed and have a lower frequency of rupture and growth rates.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] As localization of deformation among faults continues, some faults may concentrate the stress and upon linking with other faults form a main fault that accommodates most of the displacement in the region.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] On the other hand, the faults that orient in the stress shadow will decrease in growth rates and even become inactive in the long term.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] As a result, in a region with pervasive compressional stress, two merged fold segments are usually aligned along-strike, as the folds would probably be rendered inactive if they are not aligned in such favorable ways.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Amid, relative height of surface in the horizontal middle of the surface in the area of approaching fold tips, is useful for defining the status of two approaching structures in the spectrum from no linkage to linear or en-echelon linkage.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] Relative height is defined as the surface elevation of the point of interest minus the average surface elevation of the area of the approaching fold tips (see fig.15).
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] After determining the presence of linkage between twofold segments, it is possible to identify linear linkage between the segments by a straight antiformal saddle in between the two main folds.
[src:geology/3d-fold-evolution] For an en-echelon linkage, the main folds of the segments would be linked by a curved antiformal saddle in between.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Vesta is thought to be the second-largest asteroid, both by mass and by volume, after the dwarf planet Ceres.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Measurements give it a nominal volume only slightly larger than that of Pallas (about 5% greater), but it is 25% to 30% more massive.
[src:geology/4-vesta] It constitutes an estimated 9% of the mass of the asteroid belt.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Vesta is the only known remaining rocky protoplanet of the kind that formed the terrestrial planets.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Numerous fragments of Vesta were ejected by collisions one and two billion years ago that left two enormous craters occupying much of Vesta's southern hemisphere.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Debris from these events has fallen to Earth as howardite–eucrite–diogenite (HED) meteorites, which have been a rich source of information about Vesta.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Vesta is the brightest asteroid visible from Earth.
[src:geology/4-vesta] It is regularly as bright as magnitude 5.1, at which times it is faintly visible to the naked eye.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Its maximum distance from the Sun is slightly greater than the minimum distance of Ceres from the Sun, although its orbit lies entirely within that of Ceres.
[src:geology/4-vesta] NASA's *Dawn* spacecraft entered orbit around Vesta on 16 July 2011 for a one-year exploration and left the orbit of Vesta on 5 September 2012 en route to its final destination, Ceres.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Researchers continue to examine data collected by *Dawn* for additional insights into the formation and history of Vesta.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Heinrich Olbers discovered Pallas in 1802, the year after the discovery of Ceres.
[src:geology/4-vesta] He proposed that the two objects were the remnants of a destroyed planet.
[src:geology/4-vesta] He sent a letter with his proposal to the British astronomer William Herschel, suggesting that a search near the locations where the orbits of Ceres and Pallas intersected might reveal more fragments.
[src:geology/4-vesta] These orbital intersections were located in the constellations of Cetus and Virgo.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Olbers commenced his search in 1802, and on 29 March 1807 he discovered Vesta in the constellation Virgo—a coincidence, because Ceres, Pallas, and Vesta are not fragments of a larger body.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Because the asteroid Juno had been discovered in 1804, this made Vesta the fourth object to be identified in the region that is now known as the asteroid belt.
[src:geology/4-vesta] The discovery was announced in a letter addressed to German astronomer Johann H.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Gauss decided on the Roman virgin goddess of home and hearth, Vesta.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Vesta was the fourth asteroid to be discovered, hence the number 4 in its formal designation.
[src:geology/4-vesta] The name *Vesta*, or national variants thereof, is in international use with two exceptions: Greece and China.
[src:geology/4-vesta] In Greek, the name adopted was the Hellenic equivalent of Vesta, Hestia (4 Εστία); in English, that name is used for 46 Hestia (Greeks use the name "Hestia" for both, with the minor-planet numbers used for disambiguation).
[src:geology/4-vesta] In Chinese, Vesta is called the 'hearth-god(dess) star', 灶神星 **Zàoshénxīng**, naming the asteroid for Vesta's role in mythology, similar to the Chinese names of Uranus, Neptune, and Pluto.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Upon its discovery, Vesta was, like Ceres, Pallas, and Juno before it, classified as a planet and given a planetary symbol.
[src:geology/4-vesta] The symbol represented the altar of Vesta with its sacred fire and was designed by Gauss.
[src:geology/4-vesta] In Gauss's conception, now obsolete, this was drawn (Gauss's version of the astronomical symbol for Vesta).
[src:geology/4-vesta] His form was encoded in Unicode 17.0 as U+1F777 🝷.
[src:geology/4-vesta] The asteroid symbols were gradually retired from astronomical use after 1852, but the symbols for the first four asteroids were resurrected for astrology in the 1970s.
[src:geology/4-vesta] The abbreviated modern astrological variant of the Vesta symbol is (Astrological version of the astronomical symbol for Vesta) (U+26B6 ⚶).
[src:geology/4-vesta] After the discovery of Vesta, no further objects were discovered for 38 years, and during this time the Solar System was thought to have eleven planets.
[src:geology/4-vesta] However, in 1845, new asteroids started being discovered at a rapid pace, and by 1851 there were fifteen, each with its own symbol, in addition to the eight major planets (Neptune had been discovered in 1846).
[src:geology/4-vesta] It soon became clear that it would be impractical to continue inventing new planetary symbols indefinitely, and some of the existing ones proved difficult to draw quickly.
[src:geology/4-vesta] That year, the problem was addressed by Benjamin Apthorp Gould, who suggested numbering asteroids in their order of discovery, and placing this number in a disk (circle) as the generic symbol of an asteroid.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Thus, the fourth asteroid, Vesta, acquired the generic symbol ④.
[src:geology/4-vesta] This was soon coupled with the name into an official number–name designation, *④ Vesta*, as the number of minor planets increased.
[src:geology/4-vesta] By 1858, the circle had been simplified to parentheses, *(4) Vesta*, which were easier to typeset.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Other punctuation, such as *4) Vesta* and *4, Vesta*, was also briefly used, but had more or less completely died out by 1949.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Photometric observations of Vesta were made at the Harvard College Observatory in 1880–1882 and at the Observatoire de Toulouse in 1909.
[src:geology/4-vesta] These and other observations allowed the rotation rate of Vesta to be determined by the 1950s.
[src:geology/4-vesta] However, the early estimates of the rotation rate came into question because the light curve included variations in both shape and albedo.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Early estimates of the diameter of Vesta ranged from 383 kilometres (238 mi) in 1825, to 444 km (276 mi).
[src:geology/4-vesta] Pickering produced an estimated diameter of 513 ± 17 km (319 ± 11 mi) in 1879, which is close to the modern value for the mean diameter, but the subsequent estimates ranged from a low of 390 km (242 mi) up to a high of 602 km (374 mi) during the next century.
[src:geology/4-vesta] The measured estimates were based on photometry.
[src:geology/4-vesta] In 1989, speckle interferometry was used to measure a dimension that varied between 498 and 548 km (309 and 341 mi) during the rotational period.
[src:geology/4-vesta] In 1991, an occultation of the star SAO 93228 by Vesta was observed from multiple locations in the eastern United States and Canada.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Based on observations from 14 different sites, the best fit to the data was an elliptical profile with dimensions of about 550 km × 462 km (342 mi × 287 mi).
[src:geology/4-vesta] Vesta became the first asteroid to have its mass determined.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Every 18 years, the asteroid 197 Arete approaches within 0.04 AU of Vesta.
[src:geology/4-vesta] In 1966, based upon observations of Vesta's gravitational perturbations of Arete, Hans G.
[src:geology/4-vesta] More refined estimates followed, and in 2001 the perturbations of 17 Thetis were used to calculate the mass of Vesta to be (1.31±0.02)×10−10 M☉.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Vesta orbits the Sun between Mars and Jupiter, within the asteroid belt, with a period of 3.6 Earth years, specifically in the inner asteroid belt, interior to the Kirkwood gap at 2.50 AU.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Its orbit is moderately inclined (*i* = 7.1°, compared to 7° for Mercury and 17° for Pluto) and moderately eccentric (*e* = 0.09, about the same as for Mars).
[src:geology/4-vesta] True orbital resonances between asteroids are considered unlikely.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Because of their small masses relative to their large separations, such relationships should be very rare.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Nevertheless, Vesta is able to capture other asteroids into temporary 1:1 resonant orbital relationships (for periods up to 2 million years or more) and about forty such objects have been identified.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Decameter-sized objects detected in the vicinity of Vesta by *Dawn* may be such quasi-satellites rather than proper satellites.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Olbers Regio (dark area) defines the prime meridian in the IAU coordinate system.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Vesta's rotation is relatively fast for an asteroid (5.342 h) and prograde, with the north pole pointing in the direction of right ascension 20 h 32 min, declination +48° (in the constellation Cygnus) with an uncertainty of about 10°.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Two longitudinal coordinate systems are used for Vesta, with prime meridians separated by 150°.
[src:geology/4-vesta] The IAU established a coordinate system in 1997 based on *Hubble* photos, with the prime meridian running through the center of Olbers Regio, a dark feature 200 km (120 mi) across.
[src:geology/4-vesta] They corrected the pole, but also established a new prime meridian 4° from the center of Claudia, a sharply defined crater 700 m (2,300 ft) across, which they say results in a more logical set of mapping quadrangles.
[src:geology/4-vesta] All NASA publications, including images and maps of Vesta, use the Claudian meridian, which is unacceptable to the IAU.
[src:geology/4-vesta] The IAU Working Group on Cartographic Coordinates and Rotational Elements recommended a coordinate system, correcting the pole but rotating the Claudian longitude by 150° to coincide with Olbers Regio.
[src:geology/4-vesta] It was accepted by the IAU, although it disrupts the maps prepared by the *Dawn* team, which had been positioned so they would not bisect any major surface features.
[src:geology/4-vesta] The mass of 4 Vesta (dark green) compared to other large asteroids and the remainder of the Main Belt.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Vesta is the second most massive body in the asteroid belt, although it is only 28% as massive as Ceres, the most massive body.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Vesta is, however, the most massive body that formed in the asteroid belt, as Ceres is believed to have formed between Jupiter and Saturn.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Vesta's density is lower than those of the four terrestrial planets but is higher than those of most asteroids, as well as all of the moons in the Solar System except Io.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Vesta's surface area is about the same as the land area of Pakistan, Venezuela, Tanzania, or Nigeria; slightly under 900,000 km2 (350,000 mi2; 90 million ha; 220 million acres).
[src:geology/4-vesta] It has an only partially differentiated interior.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Vesta is only slightly larger (525.4±0.2 km) than 2 Pallas (512±3 km) in mean diameter, but is about 25% more massive.
[src:geology/4-vesta] A 2012 analysis of Vesta's shape and gravity field using data gathered by the *Dawn* spacecraft has shown that Vesta is currently not in hydrostatic equilibrium.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Temperatures on the surface have been estimated to lie between about −20 °C (253 K) with the Sun overhead, dropping to about −190 °C (83.1 K) at the winter pole.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Typical daytime and nighttime temperatures are −60 °C (213 K) and −130 °C (143 K), respectively.
[src:geology/4-vesta] This estimate is for 6 May 1996, very close to perihelion, although details vary somewhat with the seasons.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Before the arrival of the *Dawn* spacecraft, some Vestan surface features had already been resolved using the Hubble Space Telescope and ground-based telescopes (e.g., the Keck Observatory).
[src:geology/4-vesta] The arrival of *Dawn* in July 2011 revealed the complex surface of Vesta in detail.
[src:geology/4-vesta] The most prominent of these surface features are two enormous impact basins, the 500-kilometre-wide (311 mi) Rheasilvia, centered near the south pole; and the 400-kilometre-wide (249 mi) Veneneia.
[src:geology/4-vesta] The Rheasilvia impact basin is younger and overlies the Veneneia.
[src:geology/4-vesta] The *Dawn* science team named the younger, more prominent crater Rheasilvia, after the mother of Romulus and Remus and a mythical vestal virgin.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Its width is 95% of the mean diameter of Vesta.
[src:geology/4-vesta] A central peak rises 23 km (14 mi) above the lowest measured part of the crater floor and the highest measured part of the crater rim is 31 km (19 mi) above the crater floor low point.
[src:geology/4-vesta] It is estimated that the impact responsible excavated about 1% of the volume of Vesta, and it is likely that the Vesta family and V-type asteroids are the products of this collision.
[src:geology/4-vesta] If this is the case, then the fact that 10 km (6 mi) fragments have survived bombardment until the present indicates that the crater is at most only about 1 billion years old.
[src:geology/4-vesta] It would also be the site of origin of the HED meteorites.
[src:geology/4-vesta] All the known V-type asteroids taken together account for only about 6% of the ejected volume, with the rest presumably either in small fragments, ejected by approaching the 3:1 Kirkwood gap, or perturbed away by the Yarkovsky effect or radiation pressure.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Spectroscopic analyses of the Hubble images have shown that this crater has penetrated deep through several distinct layers of the crust, and possibly into the mantle, as indicated by spectral signatures of olivine.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Subsequent analysis of data from the Dawn mission provided much greater detail on Rheasilvia's structure and composition, confirming it as one of the largest impact structures known relative to its parent body size.
[src:geology/4-vesta] The impact clearly modified the pre-existing very large, Veneneia structure, indicating Rheasilvia's younger age.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Rheasilvia's size makes Vesta's southern topography unique, creating a flattened southern hemisphere and contributing significantly to the asteroid's overall oblate shape.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Rheasilvia's ~22 km (14 mi) central peak stands as one of the tallest mountains identified in the Solar System.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Its base width of roughly 180 km (110 mi) and complex morphology distinguishes it from the simpler central peaks seen in smaller craters.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Numerical modeling indicates that such a large central structure within a ~505 km (314 mi) diameter basin requires formation on a differentiated body with significant gravity.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Scaling laws for craters on smaller asteroids fail to predict such a feature; instead, impact dynamics involving transient crater collapse and rebound of the underlying material (potentially upper mantle) are needed to explain its formation.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Hydrocode simulations suggest the impactor responsible was likely 60–70 km (37–43 mi) across, impacting at roughly 5.4 km/s (3.4 mi/s).
[src:geology/4-vesta] Models of impact angle (around 30–45 degrees from vertical) better match the detailed morphology of the basin and its prominent peak.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Crater density measurements on Rheasilvia's relatively unmodified floor materials and surrounding ejecta deposits, calibrated using standard lunar chronology functions adapted for Vesta's location, place the impact event at approximately 1 billion years ago.
[src:geology/4-vesta] This age makes Rheasilvia a relatively young feature on a protoplanetary body formed early in Solar System history.
[src:geology/4-vesta] The estimated excavation of ~1% of Vesta's volume provides a direct link to the Vesta family of asteroids (Vestoids) and the HED meteorites.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Since Vesta's spectral signature matches that of the Vestoids and HEDs, this strongly indicates they are fragments ejected from Vesta most likely during the Rheasilvia impact.
[src:geology/4-vesta] The Dawn mission's VIR instrument helped to confirm the basin's deep excavation and compositional diversity.
[src:geology/4-vesta] VIR mapping revealed spectral variations across the basin consistent with the mixing of different crustal layers expected in the HED meteorites.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Signatures matching eucrites (shallow crustal basalts) and diogenites (deeper crustal orthopyroxenites) were identified, which usually correlate with specific morphological features like crater walls or slump blocks.
[src:geology/4-vesta] The confirmed signature of olivine-rich material, which were first hinted at by Hubble observations is strongest on the flanks of the central peak and in specific patches along the basin rim and walls, suggesting it is not uniformly distributed but rather exposed in distinct outcrops.
[src:geology/4-vesta] As the dominant mineral expected in Vesta's mantle beneath the HED-like crust, the presence of olivine indicates the Rheasilvia impact penetrated Vesta's entire crust (~20–40 km (12–25 mi) thick in the region) and excavated material from the upper mantle.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Furthermore, the global stresses resulting from this massive impact are considered the likely trigger for the formation of the large trough systems, like Divalia Fossa, that encircle Vesta's equatorial regions.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Several old, degraded craters approach Rheasilvia and Veneneia in size, although none are quite so large.
[src:geology/4-vesta] They include Feralia Planitia, shown at right, which is 270 km (168 mi) across.
[src:geology/4-vesta] More-recent, sharper craters range up to 158 km (98 mi) Varronilla and 196 km (122 mi) Postumia.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Dust fills up some craters, creating so-called dust ponds.
[src:geology/4-vesta] They are a phenomenon where pockets of dust are seen in celestial bodies without a significant atmosphere.
[src:geology/4-vesta] These are smooth deposits of dust accumulated in depressions on the surface of the body (like craters), contrasting from the Rocky terrain around them.
[src:geology/4-vesta] On the surface of Vesta, we have identified both type 1 (formed from impact melt) and type 2 (electrostatically made) dust ponds within 0˚–30°N/S, that is, Equatorial region.
[src:geology/4-vesta] 10 craters have been identified with such formations.
[src:geology/4-vesta] The "snowman craters" are a group of three adjacent craters in Vesta's northern hemisphere.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Their official names, from largest to smallest (west to east), are Marcia, Calpurnia, and Minucia.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Marcia is the youngest and cross-cuts Calpurnia.
[src:geology/4-vesta] The majority of the equatorial region of Vesta is sculpted by a series of parallel troughs designated Divalia Fossae; its longest trough is 10–20 kilometres (6.2–12.4 mi) wide and 465 kilometres (289 mi) long.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Despite the fact that Vesta is one-seventh the size of the Moon, Divalia Fossae dwarfs the Grand Canyon.
[src:geology/4-vesta] A second series, inclined to the equator, is found further north.
[src:geology/4-vesta] This northern trough system is named Saturnalia Fossae, with its largest trough being roughly 40 km (25 mi) wide and over 370 km (230 mi) long.
[src:geology/4-vesta] These troughs are thought to be large-scale graben resulting from the impacts that created Rheasilvia and Veneneia craters, respectively.
[src:geology/4-vesta] They are some of the longest chasms in the Solar System, nearly as long as Ithaca Chasma on Tethys.
[src:geology/4-vesta] The troughs may be graben that formed after another asteroid collided with Vesta, a process that can happen only in a body that is differentiated, which Vesta may not fully be.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Alternatively, it is proposed that the troughs may be radial sculptures created by secondary cratering from Rheasilvia.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Compositional information from the visible and infrared spectrometer (VIR), gamma-ray and neutron detector (GRaND), and framing camera (FC), all indicate that the majority of the surface composition of Vesta is consistent with the composition of the howardite, eucrite, and diogenite meteorites.
[src:geology/4-vesta] The Rheasilvia region is richest in diogenite, consistent with the Rheasilvia-forming impact excavating material from deeper within Vesta.
[src:geology/4-vesta] The presence of olivine within the Rheasilvia region would also be consistent with excavation of mantle material.
[src:geology/4-vesta] However, olivine has only been detected in localized regions of the northern hemisphere, not within Rheasilvia.
[src:geology/4-vesta] The origin of this olivine is currently unclear.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Though olivine was expected by astronomers to have originated from Vesta's mantle prior to the arrival of the *Dawn* orbiter, the lack of olivine within the Rheasilvia and Veneneia impact basins complicates this view.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Both impact basins excavated Vestian material down to 60–100 km (37–62 mi), far deeper than the expected thickness of ~30–40 km (19–25 mi) for Vesta's crust.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Vesta's crust may be far thicker than expected or the violent impact events that created Rheasilvia and Veneneia may have mixed material enough to obscure olivine from observations.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Alternatively, *Dawn* observations of olivine could instead be due to delivery by olivine-rich impactors, unrelated to Vesta's internal structure.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Pitted terrain has been observed in four craters on Vesta: Marcia, Cornelia, Numisia and Licinia.
[src:geology/4-vesta] The formation of the pitted terrain is proposed to be degassing of impact-heated volatile-bearing material.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Along with the pitted terrain, curvilinear gullies are found in Marcia and Cornelia craters.
[src:geology/4-vesta] The curvilinear gullies end in lobate deposits, which are sometimes covered by pitted terrain, and are proposed to form by the transient flow of liquid water after buried deposits of ice were melted by the heat of the impacts.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Hydrated materials have also been detected, many of which are associated with areas of dark material.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Consequently, dark material is thought to be largely composed of carbonaceous chondrite, which was deposited on the surface by impacts.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Carbonaceous chondrites are comparatively rich in mineralogically bound OH.
[src:geology/4-vesta] A large collection of potential samples from Vesta is accessible to scientists, in the form of over 1200 HED meteorites (Vestan achondrites), giving insight into Vesta's geologic history and structure.
[src:geology/4-vesta] NASA Infrared Telescope Facility (NASA IRTF) studies of asteroid (237442) 1999 TA10 suggest that it originated from deeper within Vesta than the HED meteorites.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Vesta is thought to consist of a metallic iron–nickel core, variously estimated to be 90 km (56 mi) to 220 km (140 mi) in diameter, an overlying rocky olivine mantle, with a surface crust of similar composition to HED meteorites.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Vesta is the only known intact asteroid that has been resurfaced in this manner.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Because of this, some scientists refer to Vesta as a protoplanet.
[src:geology/4-vesta] On the basis of the sizes of V-type asteroids (thought to be pieces of Vesta's crust ejected during large impacts), and the depth of Rheasilvia crater (see below), the crust is thought to be roughly 10 kilometres (6 mi) thick.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Findings from the *Dawn* spacecraft have found evidence that the troughs that wrap around Vesta could be graben formed by impact-induced faulting (see Troughs section above), meaning that Vesta has more complex geology than other asteroids.
[src:geology/4-vesta] The impacts that created the Rheasilvia and Veneneia craters occurred when Vesta was no longer warm and plastic enough to return to an equilibrium shape, distorting its once rounded shape and prohibiting it from being classified as a dwarf planet today.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Vesta's surface is covered by regolith distinct from that found on the Moon or asteroids such as Itokawa.
[src:geology/4-vesta] This is because space weathering acts differently.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Vesta's surface shows no significant trace of nanophase iron because the impact speeds on Vesta are too low to make rock melting and vaporization an appreciable process.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Instead, regolith evolution is dominated by brecciation and subsequent mixing of bright and dark components.
[src:geology/4-vesta] The dark component is probably due to the infall of carbonaceous material, whereas the bright component is the original Vesta basaltic soil.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Some small Solar System bodies are suspected to be fragments of Vesta caused by impacts.
[src:geology/4-vesta] The Vestian asteroids and HED meteorites are examples.
[src:geology/4-vesta] The V-type asteroid 1929 Kollaa has been determined to have a composition akin to cumulate eucrite meteorites, indicating its origin deep within Vesta's crust.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Vesta is currently one of only eight identified Solar System bodies of which we have physical samples, coming from a number of meteorites suspected to be Vestan fragments.
[src:geology/4-vesta] It is estimated that 1 out of 16 meteorites originated from Vesta.
[src:geology/4-vesta] The other identified Solar System samples are from Earth itself, meteorites from Mars, meteorites from the Moon, and samples returned from the Moon, the comet Wild 2, and the asteroids 25143 Itokawa, 162173 Ryugu, and 101955 Bennu.
[src:geology/4-vesta] In 1981, a proposal for an asteroid mission was submitted to the European Space Agency (ESA).
[src:geology/4-vesta] Named the Asteroidal Gravity Optical and Radar Analysis (AGORA), this spacecraft was to launch some time in 1990–1994 and perform two flybys of large asteroids.
[src:geology/4-vesta] The preferred target for this mission was Vesta.
[src:geology/4-vesta] AGORA would reach the asteroid belt either by a gravitational slingshot trajectory past Mars or by means of a small ion engine.
[src:geology/4-vesta] However, the proposal was refused by the ESA.
[src:geology/4-vesta] A joint NASA–ESA asteroid mission was then drawn up for a Multiple Asteroid Orbiter with Solar Electric Propulsion (MAOSEP), with one of the mission profiles including an orbit of Vesta.
[src:geology/4-vesta] NASA indicated they were not interested in an asteroid mission.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Instead, the ESA set up a technological study of a spacecraft with an ion drive.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Other missions to the asteroid belt were proposed in the 1980s by France, Germany, Italy and the United States, but none were approved.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Exploration of Vesta by fly-by and impacting penetrator was the second main target of the first plan of the multi-aimed Soviet Vesta mission, developed in cooperation with European countries for realisation in 1991–1994 but canceled due to the dissolution of the Soviet Union.
[src:geology/4-vesta] In the early 1990s, NASA initiated the Discovery Program, which was intended to be a series of low-cost scientific missions.
[src:geology/4-vesta] In 1996, the program's study team recommended a mission to explore the asteroid belt using a spacecraft with an ion engine as a high priority.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Funding for this program remained problematic for several years, but by 2004 the *Dawn* vehicle had passed its critical design review and construction proceeded.
[src:geology/4-vesta] It launched on 27 September 2007 as the first space mission to Vesta.
[src:geology/4-vesta] On 3 May 2011, *Dawn* acquired its first targeting image 1.2 million kilometres (0.75×10^6 mi) from Vesta.
[src:geology/4-vesta] On 16 July 2011, NASA confirmed that it received telemetry from *Dawn* indicating that the spacecraft successfully entered Vesta's orbit.
[src:geology/4-vesta] It was scheduled to orbit Vesta for one year, until July 2012.
[src:geology/4-vesta] *Dawn*'s arrival coincided with late summer in the southern hemisphere of Vesta, with the large crater at Vesta's south pole (Rheasilvia) in sunlight.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Because a season on Vesta lasts eleven months, the northern hemisphere, including anticipated compression fractures opposite the crater, would become visible to *Dawn*'s cameras before it left orbit.
[src:geology/4-vesta] *Dawn* left orbit around Vesta on 4 September 2012 11:26 p.m.
[src:geology/4-vesta] NASA/DLR released imagery and summary information from a survey orbit, two high-altitude orbits (60–70 m/pixel) and a low-altitude mapping orbit (20 m/pixel), including digital terrain models, videos and atlases.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Scientists also used *Dawn* to calculate Vesta's precise mass and gravity field.
[src:geology/4-vesta] The subsequent determination of the J2 component yielded a core diameter estimate of about 220 km (140 mi) assuming a crustal density similar to that of the HED.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Detailed images retrieved during the high-altitude (60–70 m/pixel) and low-altitude (~20 m/pixel) mapping orbits are available on the Dawn Mission website of JPL/NASA.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Its size and unusually bright surface make Vesta the brightest asteroid, and it is occasionally visible to the naked eye from dark skies (without light pollution).
[src:geology/4-vesta] In May and June 2007, Vesta reached a peak magnitude of +5.4, the brightest since 1989.
[src:geology/4-vesta] At that time, opposition and perihelion were only a few weeks apart.
[src:geology/4-vesta] It was brighter still at its 22 June 2018 opposition, reaching a magnitude of +5.3.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Less favorable oppositions during late autumn 2008 in the Northern Hemisphere still had Vesta at a magnitude of from +6.5 to +7.3.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Even when in conjunction with the Sun, Vesta will have a magnitude around +8.5; thus from a pollution-free sky it can be observed with binoculars even at elongations much smaller than near opposition.
[src:geology/4-vesta] In 2010, Vesta reached opposition in the constellation of Leo on the night of 17–18 February, at about magnitude 6.1, a brightness that makes it visible in binocular range but generally not for the naked eye.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Under perfect dark sky conditions where all light pollution is absent it might be visible to an experienced observer without the use of a telescope or binoculars.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Vesta came to opposition again on 5 August 2011, in the constellation of Capricornus at about magnitude 5.6.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Vesta was at opposition again on 9 December 2012.
[src:geology/4-vesta] According to *Sky and Telescope* magazine, this year Vesta came within about 6 degrees of 1 Ceres during the winter of 2012 and spring 2013.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Vesta orbits the Sun in 3.63 years and Ceres in 4.6 years, so every 17.4 years Vesta overtakes Ceres (the previous overtaking was in April 1996).
[src:geology/4-vesta] On 1 December 2012, Vesta had a magnitude of 6.6, but it had decreased to 8.4 by 1 May 2013.
[src:geology/4-vesta] Ceres and Vesta came within one degree of each other in the night sky in July 2014.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was most recently revised for its ninth edition of 1940.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] Abridged versions and a supplement exist.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was initially the basis for the 2021 *Cambridge Greek Lexicon*, although subsequently that became a complete rewrite from scratch.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] The lexicon was begun in the 19th century, and is now in its ninth (revised) edition, published in 1940.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was based on the earlier *Handwörterbuch der griechischen Sprache* by the German lexicographer Franz Passow (first published in 1819, fourth edition 1831), which in turn was based on Johann Gottlob Schneider's *Kritisches griechisch-deutsches Handwörterbuch*.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] The *Lexicon* has served as the basis for all later lexicographical work on the ancient Greek language, such as the ongoing Greek–Spanish dictionary project *Diccionario Griego–Español* (DGE).
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] It is now conventionally referred to as *Liddell & Scott*, *Liddell–Scott–Jones*, or *LSJ*, and its three sizes are sometimes referred to as "The Little Liddell", "The Middle Liddell" and "The Big Liddell" or "The Great Scott".
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] The LSJ main edition has 116,502 entries.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] According to Stuart Jones's preface to the ninth (1925) edition, the creation of the *Lexicon* was originally proposed by David Alphonso Talboys, an Oxford publisher.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was published by the Clarendon Press at Oxford rather than by Talboys, who died before the first edition (1843) was complete.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] The first editor of the LSJ, Henry George Liddell, was Dean of Christ Church, Oxford, and the father of Alice Liddell, the eponymous Alice of the writings of Lewis Carroll.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] The eighth edition (1897) was the last edition published during Liddell's lifetime.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] The LSJ is sometimes compared and contrasted with *A Latin Dictionary* by Lewis and Short, which was also published by Oxford University Press (OUP).
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] It is also sometimes compared with the Bauer lexicon, which is a similar work focused on the Greek of the New Testament.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] The LSJ's definitions reflect the Victorian morality of its time, using euphemism.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] For example, χέζω (*chezo*, 'to shit'), is translated as "ease oneself, do one's need"; βινέω (*bineo*, 'to fuck') as "inire, coire, of illicit intercourse"; and λαικάζω (*laikazo*, 'to suck cocks') as "to wench".
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] Two condensed editions of LSJ were published by Oxford University Press and remain in print.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] In 1843, the same year as the full lexicon's publication, *A Lexicon: Abridged from Liddell and Scott's Greek–English Lexicon*, sometimes called "the Little Liddell" was published.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] For example, a reprint, re-typeset in 2007, of the 1909 edition is available from Simon Wallenberg Press.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] In 1889, an intermediate edition of the lexicon, *An Intermediate Greek–English Lexicon*, was prepared on the basis of the seventh edition (1883) of LSJ.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] After the publication of the ninth edition in 1940, and shortly after the deaths of both Stuart Jones and McKenzie, the OUP maintained a list of *addenda et corrigenda* ("additions and corrections"), which was bound with subsequent printings.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] However, in 1968, these were replaced by a Supplement to the LSJ.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] Neither the *addenda* nor the Supplement has ever been merged into the main text, which still stands as originally composed by Liddell, Scott, Jones, and McKenzie.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Supplement was initially edited by M.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] Glare, editor of the *Oxford Latin Dictionary* (not to be confused with Lewis and Short's *A Latin Dictionary*).
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] Since 1988, it has been edited by Glare and Anne A.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] As the title page of the *Lexicon* makes clear (and the prefaces to the main text and to the Supplement attest), this editorial work has been performed "with the cooperation of many scholars".
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Supplement primarily takes the form of a list of additions and corrections to the main text, sorted by entry.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] The supplemental entries are marked with signs to show the nature of the changes they call for.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] Thus, a user of the *Lexicon* can consult the Supplement after consulting the main text to see whether scholarship after Jones and McKenzie has provided any new information about a particular word.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] As of 2005, the most recent revision of the Supplement, published in 1996, contains 320 pages of corrections to the main text, as well as other materials.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] The small "x" indicates that this word did not appear in the main text at all; "S.*fr*." refers to the collected fragmentary works of Sophocles.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] One interesting new source of lexicographic material in the revised Supplement is the Mycenean inscriptions.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] The ninth edition of LSJ has been freely available in electronic form since 2007, having been digitized by the Perseus Project.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] Diogenes, a free software package, incorporates the Perseus data and allows easy offline consultation of LSJ on Mac OS X, Windows, and Linux platforms.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] Marcion is another open source application that includes the Perseus LSJ.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] For mobile devices, both the Kindle E-Ink and the iPhone/iPod Touch feature data ported from Perseus.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Android market also currently offers the intermediate LSJ as an offline downloadable app for free or for a small price.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] A CD-ROM version published and sold by Logos Bible Software also incorporates the Supplement's additions to the ninth edition of LSJ.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] A new online version of LSJ was released in 2011 by the Thesaurus Linguae Graecae (TLG).
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] The TLG version corrects "a large number of typographical errors", and includes links to the extensive TLG textual corpus.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] A Kindle version, the "Complete Liddell & Scott's Lexicon with Inflections", is also available: it allows searches of most Classical Greek word-forms and supports a growing number of Ancient/Classical Greek texts for the device.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Lexicon has been translated into Modern Greek by Xenophon Moschos, ed.: Michael Konstantinidis and was published by Anestis Konstantinidis in 1904 with the title *H.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] Scott – Α.* Κωνσταντινίδου (Μέγα Λεξικόν τῆς Ἑλληνικῆς Γλώσσης).
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] Also, a supplement compiled by a group of Greek philologists.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] An Italian translation of the *Intermediate Liddell-Scott*, entitled *Dizionario illustrato Greco-Italiano* was published in 1975 by Le Monnier, edited by Q.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] LSJ was the basis of the project of John Chadwick and James Diggle at Cambridge to publish the *Cambridge Greek Lexicon* of 2021.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] Although it was initially conceived as a mere update of LSJ, the editors eventually decided to start afresh since they considered LSJ "too antiquated in concept, design and content".
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] The CGL has a smaller scope than the LSJ (and also the *Brill Dictionary of Ancient Greek*), and is unlikely to replace it; however, it is still more comprehensive than the Middle Liddell, which it intends to replace.
[src:geology/a-greek-english-lexicon] The *Cambridge Greek Lexicon* uses contemporary language for its definitions and, unlike the LSJ, no longer elides the meaning of words considered offensive in Victorian times.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The study of abiogenesis aims to determine how pre-life chemical reactions gave rise to life under conditions strikingly different from those on Earth today.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] It uses tools from biology and chemistry, attempting a synthesis of many sciences.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Life functions through the chemistry of carbon and water, and builds on four chemical families: lipids for cell membranes, carbohydrates such as sugars, amino acids for protein metabolism, and the nucleic acids DNA and RNA for heredity.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] A theory of abiogenesis must explain the origins and interactions of these classes of molecules.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Many approaches investigate how self-replicating molecules came into existence.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Researchers think that life descends from an RNA world, although other self-replicating and self-catalyzing molecules may have preceded RNA.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Other approaches ("metabolism-first" hypotheses) focus on how catalysis on the early Earth might have provided the precursor molecules for self-replication.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The 1952 Miller–Urey experiment demonstrated that amino acids can be synthesized from inorganic compounds under conditions like early Earth's.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Subsequently, amino acids have been found in meteorites, comets, asteroids, and star-forming regions of space.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] While the last universal common ancestor of all modern organisms (LUCA) existed millions of years after the origin of life, its study can guide research into early universal characteristics.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] A genomics approach has sought to characterize LUCA by identifying the genes shared by Archaea and Bacteria, major branches of life.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] It appears there are 60 proteins common to all life and 355 prokaryotic genes that trace to LUCA; their functions imply that LUCA was anaerobic with the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway, deriving energy by chemiosmosis, and used DNA, the genetic code, and ribosomes.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Earlier cells might have had a leaky membrane and been powered by a naturally occurring proton gradient near a deep-sea white smoker hydrothermal vent; or, life may have originated inside the continental crust or in water at Earth's surface.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth is the only place known to harbor life, astrobiologists assume that life exists and came into being by similar processes on other planets.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Geochemical and fossil evidence informs most studies.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The Earth was formed at 4.54 Gya, and the earliest evidence of life on Earth dates from 3.8 Gya from Western Australia.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Fossil micro-organisms may have lived in hydrothermal vent precipitates from Quebec, soon after ocean formation during the Hadean, so the process appears to have been relatively rapid in terms of geological time.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Life consists of reproduction with (heritable) variations.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] That in turn implies a suite of cellular machinery including messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Those proteins included enzymes to operate its anaerobic respiration via the Wood–Ljungdahl metabolic pathway, and a DNA polymerase to replicate its genetic material.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The challenge for origin of life researchers is to explain how such a complex and tightly interlinked system could develop by evolutionary steps, as at first sight all its parts are necessary to enable it to function.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] For example, a cell, whether the LUCA or in a modern organism, copies its DNA with the DNA polymerase enzyme, which is itself produced by translating the DNA polymerase gene in the DNA.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Neither the enzyme nor the DNA can be produced without the other.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The evolutionary process could have started with molecular self-replication, self-assembly such as of cell membranes, and autocatalysis via RNA ribozymes in an RNA world environment.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The transition of non-life to life has not been observed experimentally.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Some scientists see both life and the origin of life as aspects of the same process.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The preconditions to the development of a living cell like the LUCA are known, though disputed in detail: a habitable world is formed with a supply of minerals and liquid water and sources of free energy inflows such as our Sun and geothermal heat.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic synthesis creates a range of simple organic compounds, which are assembled into polymers such as proteins and RNA.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] On the other side, the process after the LUCA is readily understood: biological evolution caused the development of a wide range of species with varied forms and biochemical capabilities.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] However, the derivation of the LUCA from simple components is far from understood.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth remains the only place where life is known, the science of astrobiology seeks evidence of life on other planets.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The advent of such polymers was most likely a critical step in prebiotic chemical evolution.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Those polymers derived, in turn, from simple organic compounds such as nucleobases, amino acids, and sugars, likely formed by reactions in the environment.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] A successful theory of the origin of life must explain how all these chemicals came into being.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] One ancient view of the origin of life, from Aristotle until the 19th century, was of spontaneous generation.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] This held that "lower" animals such as insects were generated by decaying organic substances, and that life arose by chance.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] This was questioned from the 17th century, in works like Thomas Browne's *Pseudodoxia Epidemica*.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1665, Robert Hooke published the first drawings of a microorganism.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1676, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek drew and described microorganisms, probably protozoa and bacteria.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Van Leeuwenhoek disagreed with spontaneous generation, and by the 1680s convinced himself, using experiments ranging from sealed and open meat incubation and the close study of insect reproduction, that the theory was incorrect.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1668 Francesco Redi showed that no maggots appeared in meat when flies were prevented from laying eggs.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] By the middle of the 19th century, spontaneous generation was considered disproven.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Dating back to Anaxagoras in the 5th century BC, panspermia is the idea that life originated elsewhere in the universe and came to Earth.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The modern version of panspermia holds that life may have been distributed to Earth by meteoroids, asteroids, comets or planetoids.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] This shifts the origin of life to another heavenly body.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The advantage is that life is not required to have formed on each planet it occurs on, but in a more limited set of locations, and then spread about the galaxy to other star systems.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] There is some interest in the possibility that life originated on Mars and later transferred to Earth.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The idea that life originated from non-living matter in slow stages appeared in Herbert Spencer's 1864–1867 book *Principles of Biology*, and in William Turner Thiselton-Dyer's 1879 paper "On spontaneous generation and evolution".
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane in 1929 proposed that the earliest cells slowly self-organized from a primordial soup, the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane suggested that the Earth's prebiotic oceans consisted of a "hot dilute soup" in which organic compounds could have formed.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Bernal showed that such mechanisms could form most of the necessary molecules for life from inorganic precursors.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1967, he suggested three "stages": the origin of biological monomers; the origin of biological polymers; and the evolution from molecules to cells.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1952, Stanley Miller and Harold Urey carried out a chemical experiment to demonstrate how organic molecules could have formed spontaneously from inorganic precursors under prebiotic conditions like those posited by the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] It passed an electric current through a highly reducing (lacking oxygen) mixture of gases—methane, ammonia, and hydrogen, with water vapor—to form organic monomers such as amino acids.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The addition of iron and carbonate minerals, present in early oceans, produces a diverse array of amino acids.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Later work has focused on two other potential reducing environments: outer space and deep-sea hydrothermal vents.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after the Big Bang, roughly 14 Gya, the only chemical elements present in the universe were hydrogen, helium, and lithium, the three lightest atoms in the periodic table.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] These elements gradually condensed into vast clouds of gas, which collapsed under gravity into rotating protostellar disks.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Gravitational accretion of material at the hot and dense centers of these disks formed the first stars by the fusion of hydrogen.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Early stars were massive and short-lived, producing all the heavier elements by stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Such element formation proceeds to its most stable element Iron-56.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Heavier elements were formed during supernovas at the end of a star's lifecycle.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon, currently the fourth most abundant element in the universe, was formed mainly in white dwarf stars.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] As these stars reached the end of their lifecycles, they ejected heavier elements, including carbon and oxygen, throughout the universe.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] These allowed for the formation of rocky planets.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] According to the nebular hypothesis, the Solar System began to form 4.6 Gya with the gravitational collapse of part of a giant molecular cloud.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Most of the collapsing mass collected in the center, forming the Sun, while the rest flattened into a protoplanetary disk out of which the planets formed.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The age of the Earth is 4.54 Gya as found by radiometric dating of calcium-aluminium-rich inclusions in carbonaceous chrondrite meteorites, the oldest material in the Solar System.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Earth, during the Hadean eon (from its formation until 4.031 Gya,) was at first inhospitable to life.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] During its formation, the Earth lost much of its initial mass, and so lacked the gravity to hold molecular hydrogen and the bulk of the original inert gases.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after initial accretion of Earth at 4.48 Gya, its collision with Theia, a hypothesised impactor, is thought to have created the ejected debris that eventually formed the Moon.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] This impact removed the Earth's primary atmosphere, leaving behind clouds of viscous silicates and carbon dioxide.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] This unstable atmosphere was short-lived, soon condensing to form the bulk silicate Earth, leaving behind an atmosphere largely consisting of water vapor, nitrogen, and carbon dioxide, with smaller amounts of carbon monoxide, hydrogen, and sulfur compounds.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The solution of carbon dioxide in water is thought to have made the seas slightly acidic, with a pH of about 5.5.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Condensation to form liquid oceans is theorised to have occurred as early as the Moon-forming impact.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] This scenario is supported by the dating of 4.404 Gya zircon crystals with high *δ*18O values from metamorphosed quartzite of Mount Narryer in Western Australia.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The Hadean atmosphere has been characterized as a "gigantic, productive outdoor chemical laboratory," similar to volcanic gases today which still support some abiotic chemistry.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Despite the likely increased volcanism from early plate tectonics, the Earth may have been a predominantly water world between 4.4 and 4.3 Gya.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] It is debated whether crust was exposed above this ocean.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Immediately after the Moon-forming impact, Earth likely had little if any continental crust, a turbulent atmosphere, and a hydrosphere subject to intense ultraviolet light from a T Tauri stage Sun.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] It was also affected by cosmic radiation, and continued asteroid and comet impacts.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The Late Heavy Bombardment hypothesis posits that a period of intense impact occurred at 4.1 to 3.8 Gya during the Hadean and early Archean eons.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Originally it was thought that the Late Heavy Bombardment was a single cataclysmic impact event occurring at 3.9 Gya; this would have had the potential to sterilize Earth by volatilizing liquid oceans and blocking sunlight needed for photosynthesis, delaying the earliest possible emergence of life.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] More recent research questioned the intensity of the Late Heavy Bombardment and its potential for sterilisation.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] If it was not one giant impact but a period of raised impact rate, it would have had much less destructive power.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The 3.9 Gya date arose from dating of Apollo mission sample returns collected mostly near the Imbrium Basin, biasing the age of recorded impacts.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Impact modelling of the lunar surface reveals that rather than a cataclysmic event at 3.9 Gya, multiple small-scale, short-lived periods of bombardment likely occurred.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Terrestrial data backs this idea by showing multiple periods of ejecta in the rock record both before and after the 3.9 Gya marker, suggesting that the early Earth was subject to continuous impacts with less impact on extinction.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from late impacts and the then high levels of ultraviolet radiation from the sun.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The available energy is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Based on evidence from the geologic record, life most likely emerged on Earth between 4.32 and 3.48 Gya.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] In 2017, the earliest physical evidence of life was reported to consist of microbialites in the Nuvvuagittuq Greenstone Belt of Northern Quebec, in banded iron formation rocks at least 3.77 and possibly as old as 4.32 Gya.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The micro-organisms could have lived within hydrothermal vent precipitates, soon after the 4.4 Gya formation of oceans during the Hadean.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The microbes resemble modern hydrothermal vent bacteria, supporting the view that abiogenesis began in such an environment.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Later research disputed this interpretation of the data, stating that the observations may be better explained by abiotic processes in silica-rich waters, "chemical gardens," circulating hydrothermal fluids, or volcanic ejecta.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Biogenic graphite has been found in 3.7 Gya metasedimentary rocks from southwestern Greenland and in microbial mat fossils from 3.49 Gya cherts in the Pilbara region of Western Australia.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Evidence of early life in rocks from Akilia Island, near the Isua supracrustal belt in southwestern Greenland, dating to 3.7 Gya, have shown biogenic carbon isotopes.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] In other parts of the Isua supracrustal belt, graphite inclusions trapped within garnet crystals are connected to the other elements of life: oxygen, nitrogen, and possibly phosphorus in the form of phosphate, providing further evidence for life 3.7 Gya.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] In the Pilbara region of Western Australia, compelling evidence of early life was found in pyrite-bearing sandstone in a fossilized beach, with rounded tubular cells that oxidized sulfur by photosynthesis in the absence of oxygen.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon isotope ratios on graphite inclusions from the Jack Hills zircons suggest that life could have existed on Earth from 4.1 Gya.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 study inferred LUCA's age as around 4.2 Gya (4.09–4.33 Gya) by analysing pre-LUCA gene duplicates, with calibration from fossil micro-organisms, much sooner after the origin of life than previously thought.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The Pilbara region of Western Australia contains the Dresser Formation with rocks 3.48 Gya, including layered structures called stromatolites.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Their modern counterparts are created by photosynthetic micro-organisms including cyanobacteria.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] These lie within undeformed hydrothermal-sedimentary strata; their texture indicates a biogenic origin.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Parts of the Dresser formation preserve hot springs on land, but other regions seem to have been shallow seas.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] A molecular clock analysis suggests the LUCA emerged prior to 3.9 Gya.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] All chemical elements derive from stellar nucleosynthesis except for hydrogen and some helium and lithium.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Basic chemical ingredients of life – the carbon-hydrogen molecule (CH), the carbon-hydrogen positive ion (CH+) and the carbon ion (C+) – can be produced by ultraviolet light from stars.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Complex molecules, including organic molecules, form naturally both in space and on planets.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] An organic compound is a chemical whose molecules contain carbon.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets of the Solar System.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds are relatively common in space, formed by "factories of complex molecular synthesis" which occur in molecular clouds and circumstellar envelopes, and chemically evolve after reactions are initiated mostly by ionizing radiation.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Purine and pyrimidine nucleobases including guanine, adenine, cytosine, uracil, and thymine, as well as sugars, have been found in meteorites.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] These could have provided the materials for DNA and RNA to form on the early Earth.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The amino acid glycine was found in material ejected from comet Wild 2; it had earlier been detected in meteorites.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Comets are encrusted with dark material, thought to be a tar-like organic substance formed from simple carbon compounds under ionizing radiation.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] A rain of material from comets could have brought such complex organic molecules to Earth.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] During the Late Heavy Bombardment, meteorites may have delivered up to five million tons of organic prebiotic elements to Earth per year.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Currently 40,000 tons of cosmic dust falls to Earth each year.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH) are the most common and abundant polyatomic molecules in the observable universe, and are a major store of carbon.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] They seem to have formed shortly after the Big Bang, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] They are a likely constituent of Earth's primordial sea.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs have been detected in nebulae, and in the interstellar medium, in comets, and in meteorites.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] A star, HH 46-IR, resembling the sun early in its life, is surrounded by a disk of material which contains molecules including cyanide compounds, hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs in the interstellar medium can be transformed through hydrogenation, oxygenation, and hydroxylation to more complex organic compounds used in living cells.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds introduced on Earth by interstellar dust particles can help to form complex molecules, thanks to their peculiar surface-catalytic activities.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA component uracil and related molecules, including xanthine, in the Murchison meteorite were likely formed extraterrestrially, as suggested by studies of 12C/13C isotopic ratios.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] NASA studies of meteorites suggest that all four DNA nucleobases (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) have been formed in outer space.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The cosmic dust permeating the universe contains complex organics ("amorphous organic solids with a mixed aromatic–aliphatic structure") that could be created rapidly by stars.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Glycolaldehyde, a sugar molecule and RNA precursor, has been detected in regions of space including around protostars and on meteorites.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] As early as the 1860s, experiments demonstrated that biologically relevant molecules can be produced from interaction of simple carbon sources with abundant inorganic catalysts.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The spontaneous formation of complex polymers from abiotically generated monomers under the conditions posited by the "soup" theory is not straightforward.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Besides the necessary basic organic monomers, compounds that would have prohibited the formation of polymers were also formed in high concentration during the Miller–Urey experiment and Joan Oró experiments.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Biology uses essentially 20 amino acids for its coded protein enzymes, representing a very small subset of the structurally possible products.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Since life tends to use whatever is available, an explanation is needed for why the set used is so small.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide is attractive as a medium that potentially provided a source of amino acid derivatives from simple aldehyde and nitrile feedstocks.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Alexander Butlerov showed in 1861 that the formose reaction created sugars including tetroses, pentoses, and hexoses when formaldehyde is heated under basic conditions with divalent metal ions like calcium.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Breslow proposed that the reaction was autocatalytic in 1959.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Nucleobases, such as guanine and adenine, can be synthesized from simple carbon and nitrogen sources, such as hydrogen cyanide (HCN) and ammonia.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] On early Earth, HCN was likely supplied via photochemical production in a transient, highly reducing atmosphere after major impacts.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide, from the reaction of water and HCN, produces all four ribonucleotides when warmed with terrestrial minerals.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] HCN can contribute to chemical processes such as the synthesis of the amino acid glycine.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] DNA and RNA components including uracil, cytosine and thymine can be synthesized under outer space conditions, using starting chemicals such as pyrimidine from meteorites.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Pyrimidine may have formed in red giant stars, interstellar dust, or gas clouds, or on Earth via precursors such as cyanoacetylene following asteroid impacts.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] All four RNA-bases may be synthesized from formamide in high-energy density events like extraterrestrial impacts.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Several ribonucleotides for RNA formation have been synthesized in a laboratory environment which replicates prebiotic conditions via autocatalytic formose reaction.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Other pathways for synthesizing bases from inorganic materials have been reported.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Freezing temperatures assist the synthesis of purines, by concentrating key precursors such as HCN.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] However, while adenine and guanine require freezing conditions, cytosine and uracil may require boiling temperatures.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Seven amino acids and eleven types of nucleobases formed in ice when ammonia and cyanide were left in a freezer for 25 years.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] S-triazines (alternative nucleobases), pyrimidines including cytosine and uracil, and adenine can be synthesized by subjecting a urea solution to freeze-thaw cycles under a reductive atmosphere with spark discharges.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] These low-temperature reactions proceed rapidly due to eutectic freezing, which crowds impurities in microscopic pockets of liquid within the ice.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic peptide synthesis could have occurred by several routes.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Some center on high temperature/concentration conditions in which condensation becomes energetically favorable, while others use plausible prebiotic condensing agents.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Experimental evidence for the formation of peptides in uniquely concentrated environments is bolstered by work suggesting that wet-dry cycles and the presence of specific salts can greatly increase spontaneous condensation of glycine into poly-glycine chains.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Other work suggests that while mineral surfaces, such as those of pyrite, calcite, and rutile catalyze peptide condensation, they also catalyze their hydrolysis.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The authors suggest that additional chemical activation or coupling would be necessary to produce peptides at sufficient concentrations.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Thus, mineral surface catalysis, while important, is not sufficient alone for peptide synthesis.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Many prebiotically plausible condensing/activating agents have been identified, including the following: cyanamide, dicyanamide, dicyandiamide, diaminomaleonitrile, urea, trimetaphosphate, NaCl, CuCl2, (Ni,Fe)S, CO, carbonyl sulfide (COS), carbon disulfide (CS2), SO2, and diammonium phosphate (DAP).
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 experiment used a sapphire substrate with a web of thin cracks under a heat flow, mimicking deep-ocean vents, to concentrate prebiotically-relevant building blocks from a dilute mixture by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] This could help to create biopolymers such as peptides.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] A similar role has been suggested for clays, though this speculation has not been supported through experimental evidence.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The prebiotic synthesis of peptides from simpler molecules such as CO, NH3 and C, skipping the step of amino acid formation, is also very efficient.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The largest unanswered question in evolution is how simple protocells first arose and differed in reproductive contribution to the following generation, thus initiating evolution.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The lipid world theory postulates that the first self-replicating object was lipid-like.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Phospholipids form lipid bilayers (as in cell membranes) in water while under agitation.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] These molecules were not present on early Earth, but other membrane-forming amphiphilic long-chain molecules were.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] These bodies may expand by insertion of additional lipids, and may spontaneously split into two offspring of similar size and composition.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Lipid bodies may have provided sheltering envelopes for information storage, allowing the evolution of information-storing polymers like RNA.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Only one or two types of vesicle-forming amphiphiles have been studied.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Such site/compound pairs are transmissible to the daughter vesicles, leading to the emergence of distinct lineages of vesicles, subject to natural selection.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] A protocell is a self-organized, self-ordered, spherical collection of lipids proposed as a stepping-stone to life, that is capable of evolving.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembled vesicles are essential components of primitive cells.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The theory of classical irreversible thermodynamics treats self-assembly under a generalized chemical potential within the framework of dissipative systems.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that overall entropy increases, yet life is distinguished by its great degree of organization.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Therefore, a boundary is needed to separate ordered life processes from chaotic non-living matter.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] A functional protocell, which must exhibit Darwinian evolution, has not yet been achieved in a laboratory setting.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Szostak suggest that elementary protocells can give rise to primitive forms of differential reproduction, competition, and energy storage.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Competition for membrane molecules would favor stabilized membranes, suggesting a selective advantage for cross-linked fatty acids and even modern phospholipids.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Such micro-encapsulation would allow for metabolism within the membrane and the exchange of small molecules, while retaining large biomolecules inside.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Such a membrane is needed for a cell to create its own electrochemical gradient.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Vesicles can undergo an evolutionary process under pressure cycling conditions.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Simulating the systemic environment in tectonic fault zones within the Earth's crust, pressure cycling forms vesicles periodically, as well as random peptide chains which are selected for ability to integrate into the vesicle membrane.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Further selection of vesicles for stability could lead to functional peptide structures, increasing vesicle survival rate.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Life requires a loss of entropy, or disorder, as molecules organize themselves into living matter.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] At the same time, the emergence of life is associated with the formation of structures beyond a certain threshold of complexity.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Multiple sources of energy were available for chemical reactions on the early Earth.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Heat from geothermal processes is a standard energy source for chemistry.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Other examples include sunlight, lightning, atmospheric entries of micro-meteorites, and implosion of bubbles in sea and ocean waves.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] This has been confirmed by experiments and simulations.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Unfavorable reactions can be driven by highly favorable ones, as in the case of iron-sulfur chemistry.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] For example, this was probably important for carbon fixation.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon fixation by reaction of CO2 with H2S via iron-sulfur chemistry is favorable, and occurs at neutral pH and 100 °C.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Iron-sulfur surfaces, which are abundant near hydrothermal vents, can drive the production of small amounts of amino acids and other biomolecules.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1961, Peter Mitchell proposed chemiosmosis as a cell's primary system of energy conversion.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism, now ubiquitous in living cells, powers energy conversion in micro-organisms and in the mitochondria of eukaryotes, making it a likely candidate for early life.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Mitochondria produce adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the energy currency of the cell used to drive cellular processes such as chemical syntheses.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism of ATP synthesis involves a closed membrane in which the ATP synthase enzyme is embedded.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The energy required to release strongly bound ATP has its origin in protons that move across the membrane.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] In modern cells, those proton movements are caused by the pumping of ions across the membrane, maintaining an electrochemical gradient.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] However, as yet, the hypothesis is untested.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA world hypothesis describes an early Earth with self-replicating and catalytic RNA but no DNA or proteins.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] It was proposed in 1962 by Alexander Rich; the term was coined by Walter Gilbert in 1986.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Many researchers concur that an RNA world must have preceded modern DNA-based life.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] However, it may not have been the first to exist.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] There may have been over 30 chemical events between pre-RNA world to near-LUCA, just involving RNA.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] RNA is central to the translation process.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Small RNAs can catalyze all the chemical groups and information transfers required for life.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] RNA both expresses and maintains genetic information in modern organisms; its components are easily synthesized under early Earth conditions.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The structure of the ribosome has been called the "smoking gun", with a central core of RNA and no amino acid side chains within 18 Å of the active site that catalyzes peptide bond formation.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] RNA replicase can both code and catalyse further RNA replication, i.e. it is autocatalytic.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Some catalytic RNAs can link smaller RNA sequences together, enabling self-replication.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Natural selection would then favor the proliferation of such autocatalytic sets.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembly of RNA may occur spontaneously in hydrothermal vents.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] A preliminary form of tRNA could have assembled into a replicator molecule.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] When this began to replicate, it may have had all three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation, and differential reproduction.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Its fitness would have depended on its ability to adapt, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and resource availability.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Starting with the work of Carl Woese from 1977, genomics studies have placed the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all modern life-forms between Bacteria and a clade formed by Archaea and Eukaryota in the phylogenetic tree of life.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] A minority of studies have placed the LUCA in Bacteria, proposing that Archaea and Eukaryota are evolutionarily derived from within Eubacteria; Thomas Cavalier-Smith suggested in 2006 that the phenotypically diverse bacterial phylum Chloroflexota contained the LUCA.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] In 2016, a set of 355 genes likely present in the LUCA was identified.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] A total of 6.1 million prokaryotic genes from Bacteria and Archaea were sequenced, identifying 355 protein clusters from among 286,514 protein clusters that were probably common to the LUCA.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The results suggest that the LUCA was anaerobic with a Wood–Ljungdahl (reductive Acetyl-CoA) pathway, nitrogen- and carbon-fixing, thermophilic.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Its cofactors suggest dependence upon an environment rich in hydrogen, carbon dioxide, iron, and transition metals.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Its genetic material was probably DNA, requiring the 4-nucleotide genetic code, messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins such as enzymes.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] LUCA likely inhabited an anaerobic hydrothermal vent setting in a geochemically active environment.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] It was evidently already a complex organism, and must have had precursors; it was not the first living thing.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] The physiology of LUCA has been in dispute.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Previous research identified 60 proteins common to all life.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p01] Metabolic reactions inferred in LUCA are the incomplete reverse Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, the pentose phosphate pathway, glycolysis, reductive amination, and transamination.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] A variety of geologic and environmental settings have been proposed for an origin of life.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] These theories are often in competition with one another as there are many views of prebiotic compound availability, geophysical setting, and early life characteristics.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] The first organism on Earth likely differed from LUCA.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Between the first appearance of life and where all modern phylogenies began branching, an unknown amount of time passed, with unknown gene transfers, extinctions, and adaptation to environmental niches.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Modern phylogenies provide more genetic evidence about LUCA than about its precursors.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Early micro-fossils may have come from a hot world of gases such as methane, ammonia, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen sulfide, toxic to much current life.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Analysis of the tree of life places thermophilic and hyperthermophilic bacteria and archaea closest to the root, suggesting that life may have evolved in a hot environment.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] The deep sea or alkaline hydrothermal vent theory posits that life began at submarine hydrothermal vents.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] William Martin and Michael Russell have suggested that this could have been in metal-sulphide-walled compartments acting as precursors for cell walls.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] These form where hydrogen-rich fluids emerge from below the sea floor, as a result of serpentinization of ultra-mafic olivine with seawater and a pH interface with carbon dioxide-rich ocean water.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] The vents form a sustained chemical energy source derived from redox reactions, in which electron donors (molecular hydrogen) react with electron acceptors (carbon dioxide); see iron–sulfur world theory.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Russell demonstrated that alkaline vents create an abiogenic proton motive force chemiosmotic gradient, ideal for abiogenesis.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Their microscopic compartments "provide a natural means of concentrating organic molecules," composed of iron-sulfur minerals such as mackinawite, endowed these mineral cells with the catalytic properties envisaged by Günter Wächtershäuser.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Electrostatic force caused by electrical potential gradient—cations like protons H+ diffuse down the electrical potential, anions in the opposite direction.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] These two gradients together can be expressed as an electrochemical gradient, providing energy for abiogenic synthesis.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] The proton motive force measures the potential energy stored as proton and voltage gradients across a membrane (differences in proton concentration and electrical potential).
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] In 2016, Martin suggested that the LUCA "may have depended heavily on the geothermal energy of the vent to survive".
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] That same year, RNA was produced in synthetic alkaline hydrothermal chimneys simulating deep-sea vents.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Researchers were able to generate RNA oligomers of up to 4 units in length.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] This RNA was synthesized using activated ribonucleotides.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Additionally, these RNA oligomers could only be synthesized under certain conditions.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Pores at deep sea hydrothermal vents are suggested to have been occupied by membrane-bound compartments which promoted biochemical reactions.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Metabolic intermediates in the Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, amino acid bio-synthetic pathways, glycolysis, the pentose phosphate pathway, and including sugars like ribose, and lipid precursors can occur non-enzymatically at conditions relevant to deep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] If the deep marine hydrothermal setting was the site, then life could have arisen as early as 4.0–4.2 Gya.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from impacts and the then high levels of solar ultraviolet radiation.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] The available energy in hydrothermal vents is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Hyperthermophily could have been a result of convergent evolution in bacteria and archaea; a mesophilic environment has been called more likely.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Production of prebiotic organic compounds at hydrothermal vents is estimated to be 108 kg/yr.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Key prebiotic compounds, such as methane are in far lower concentrations at vents than in a Miller-Urey Experiment environment.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Some organic compounds are now understood to have been formed by other geological processes and inherited by vents.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Methane, for example, more likely comes from leached fluid inclusions formed deeper in oceanic crust from magmatic carbon.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Vents do not concentrate prebiotic materials, due to strong dilution by seawater.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] This open system cycles compounds through vent minerals, leaving little residence time to accumulate.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] All modern cells rely on phosphates for nucleotide backbone and potassium for protein formation, making it likely that the first life forms shared these functions.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] These elements were not available in high quantities in the Archaean oceans.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] However, phosphate can be concentrated in lakes, as in the modern Last Chance Lake.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Submarine hydrothermal vents are not conducive to condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] An older argument was that key polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation, which supposedly would not happen in saltwater.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] However, while salinity inhibits vesicle formation from low-diversity mixtures of fatty acids, vesicle formation from a broader, more realistic mix of fatty-acid and 1-alkanol species is more resilient.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] No studies have been able to experimentally demonstrate synthesis of sugars, amino acids, nucleases, nucleosides, nucleotides, or membrane-forming fatty acids under plausible vent conditions.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Surface bodies of water provide environments that dry out and rewet.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Wet-dry cycles concentrate prebiotic compounds and enable condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, lakes and ponds receive detrital input from weathering of continental apatite-containing rocks, the most common source of phosphates.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] The amount of exposed continental crust in the Hadean is unknown, but models of early ocean depths and rates of ocean island and continental crust growth make it plausible that there was exposed land.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Another line of evidence for a surface start to life is the requirement for Ultraviolet radiation (UV) for organism function.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] UV is necessary for the formation of the U+C nucleotide base pair by partial hydrolysis and nucleobase loss.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Simultaneously, UV can be harmful and sterilising to life, especially for simple early lifeforms with little ability to repair radiation damage.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Radiation levels from a young Sun were likely greater, and, with no ozone layer, harmful shortwave UV rays would reach the surface of Earth.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] For life to begin, a shielded environment with influx from UV-exposed sources is necessary to both benefit and protect from UV.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Shielding under ice, liquid water, mineral surfaces (e.g. clay) or regolith is possible in a range of surface water settings.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Most branching phylogenies are thermophilic or hyperthermophilic, making it possible that LUCA and preceding lifeforms were similarly thermophilic.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs are formed from the heating of groundwater by geothermal activity.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] This intersection allows for influxes of material from deep penetrating waters and from surface runoff that transports eroded continental sediments.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Interconnected groundwater systems create a mechanism for distribution of life to wider area.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Mulkidjanian and co-authors argue that marine environments did not provide the ionic balance and composition universally found in cells, or the ions required by essential proteins and ribozymes, especially with respect to high K+/Na+ ratio, Mn2+, Zn2+ and phosphate concentrations.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] They argue that the only environments that do this are hot springs similar to ones at Kamchatka.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] The hypothesized pre-biotic environments are similar to hydrothermal vents, with additional components that help explain peculiarities of the LUCA.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] A phylogenomic and geochemical analysis of proteins plausibly traced to the LUCA shows that the ionic composition of its intracellular fluid is identical to that of hot springs.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] The LUCA likely was dependent upon synthesized organic matter for its growth.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments show that RNA-like polymers can be synthesized in wet-dry cycling and UV light exposure.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] These polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Potential sources of organics at hot springs might have been transported by interplanetary dust particles, extraterrestrial projectiles, or atmospheric or geochemical synthesis.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs could have been abundant in volcanic landmasses during the Hadean.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] A mesophilic start in surface bodies of waters hypothesis has evolved from Darwin's concept of a 'warm little pond' and the Oparin-Haldane hypothesis.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Freshwater bodies under temperate climates can accumulate prebiotic materials while providing suitable environmental conditions conducive to simple life forms.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Atmospheric reconstructions from geochemical proxies and models suggest that sufficient greenhouse gases were present to maintain surface temperatures between 0–40 °C.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] If so, the temperature was suitable for life to begin.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Evidence for mesophily from biomolecular studies includes Galtier's G+C nucleotide thermometer.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] G+C are more abundant in thermophiles due to the added stability of an additional hydrogen bond not present between A+T nucleotides. rRNA sequencing of modern lifeforms shows that LUCA's reconstructed G+C content was likely representative of moderate temperatures.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] The diversity of thermophiles today could be a product of convergent evolution and horizontal gene transfer rather than an inherited trait from LUCA.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] The reverse gyrase topoisomerase is found exclusively in thermophiles and hyperthermophiles, as it allows for coiling of DNA.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] This enzyme requires the complex molecule ATP to function.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] If an origin of life is hypothesised to involve a simple organism that had not yet evolved a membrane, let alone ATP, this would make the existence of reverse gyrase improbable.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, phylogenetic studies show that reverse gyrase originated in archaea, and transferred to bacteria by horizontal gene transfer, implying it was not present in the LUCA.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Cold-start theories presuppose large ice-covered regions.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Stellar evolution models predict that the Sun's luminosity was ≈25% weaker than it is today.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Fuelner states that although this significant decrease in solar energy would have formed an icy planet, there is strong evidence for the presence of liquid water, possibly driven by a greenhouse effect.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] This would mean an early Earth with both liquid oceans and icy poles.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Ice melts that form from ice sheets or glacier melts create freshwater pools, another niche capable of wet-dry cycles.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] While surface pools would be exposed to intense UV radiation, bodies of water within and under ice would be shielded, while remaining connected to exposed areas through ice cracks.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Impact melting would allow freshwater and meteoritic input, creating prebiotic components.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Near-seawater levels of sodium chloride destabilize fatty acid membrane self-assembly, making freshwater settings appealing for early membranous life.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Icy environments would trade the faster reaction rates that occur in warm environments for increased stability and accumulation of larger polymers.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments simulating Europa-like conditions of ≈20 °C have synthesised amino acids and adenine, showing that Miller-Urey type syntheses can occur at low temperatures.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] In an RNA world, the ribozyme would have had even more functions than in a later DNA-RNA-protein-world.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] For RNA to function, it must be able to fold, a process hindered by temperatures above 30 °C.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] While RNA folding in psychrophilic organisms is slower, so is hydrolysis, so folding is more successful.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Shorter nucleotides would not suffer from higher temperatures.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] The continental crust, with tectonic fault zones could present a stable and well-protected environment for long-term prebiotic evolution.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Inside these systems of cracks and cavities, water and carbon dioxide present the bulk solvents.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Their phase state could vary between liquid, gaseous and supercritical, depending on pressure and temperature.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] When forming two separate phases, the system provides optimal conditions for phase transfer reactions.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Concurrently, the contents of the tectonic fault zones are supplied with inorganic educts (e.g. carbon monoxide, hydrogen, ammonia, hydrogen cyanide, nitrogen, and phosphate) and simple organic molecules (e.g. amino acids, long-chain amines, fatty acids, long-chain aldehydes).
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Part of the tectonic fault zones is at a depth of around 1000 m.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] For carbon dioxide, it provides temperature and pressure conditions near the phase transition point between the supercritical and the gaseous state.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] This allows lipophilic organic molecules that dissolve well in supercritical CO2 to accumulate, leading to local precipitation.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Periodic pressure variations such as caused by geysers or tidal influences result in periodic phase transitions, keeping the local reaction environment in a constant non-equilibrium state.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] In presence of amphiphilic compounds (such as the long chain amines and fatty acids), subsequent generations of vesicles are formed that are selected for their stability.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Homochirality is the uniformity of materials composed of chiral (non-mirror-symmetric) units.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Living organisms use molecules with the same chirality: with almost no exceptions, amino acids are left-handed while nucleotides and sugars are right-handed.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Chiral molecules can be synthesized, but in the absence of a chiral source or a chiral catalyst, they are formed in a 50/50 (racemic) mixture of both forms.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Non-racemic mixtures can arise from racemic materials by asymmetric physical laws such as the electroweak interaction, or in asymmetric environments, such as those in which molecules are exposed to circularly polarized light of a given handedness.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] It has been hypothesized that the solar nebula was such an environment, exposed to circularly-polarized radiation from an external source before or during the epoch of planet formation.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] This proposal is consistent with the finding that some amino acids delivered to Earth in meteorites exhibit a chiral asymmetry of the same sign as terrestrial life.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] Once established, a chirality imbalance may influence subsequent chemical evolution.
[src:geology/abiogenesis-p02] A small bias in the population can be amplified by asymmetric autocatalysis, as in the Soai reaction, where a chiral molecule catalyzes its own production.
[src:geology/geology] Geology describes the structure of the Earth on and beneath its surface and the processes that have shaped that structure.
[src:geology/geology] Geologists study the mineralogical composition of rocks in order to get insight into their history of formation.
[src:geology/geology] Geology determines the relative ages of rocks found at a given location; geochemistry (a branch of geology) determines their absolute ages.
[src:geology/geology] By combining various petrological, crystallographic, and paleontological tools, geologists are able to chronicle the geological history of the Earth as a whole.
[src:geology/geology] One aspect is to demonstrate the age of the Earth.
[src:geology/geology] Geology provides evidence for plate tectonics, the evolutionary history of life, and the Earth's past climates.
[src:geology/geology] Geologists broadly study the properties and processes of Earth and other terrestrial planets.
[src:geology/geology] Geologists use a wide variety of methods to understand the Earth's structure and evolution, including fieldwork, rock description, geophysical techniques, chemical analysis, physical experiments, and numerical modelling.
[src:geology/geology] In practical terms, geology is important for mineral and hydrocarbon exploration and exploitation, evaluating water resources, understanding natural hazards, remediating environmental problems, and providing insights into past climate change.
[src:geology/geology] Geology is a major academic discipline, and it is central to geological engineering and plays an important role in geotechnical engineering.
[src:geology/geology] The majority of geological data comes from research on solid Earth materials.
[src:geology/geology] Meteorites and other extraterrestrial natural materials are also studied by geological methods.
[src:geology/geology] Minerals are naturally occurring elements and compounds with a definite homogeneous chemical composition and an ordered atomic arrangement.
[src:geology/geology] Amorphous substances that resemble a mineral are sometimes referred to as mineraloids, although there are exceptions such as georgeite and autunite.
[src:geology/geology] Some amorphous substances formed by geological processes are considered minerals if the original substance was a mineral before metamictisation.
[src:geology/geology] Each mineral has distinct physical properties, and there are many tests to determine each of them.
[src:geology/geology] Minerals are often identified through these tests.
[src:geology/geology] A rock is any naturally occurring solid mass or aggregate of minerals or mineraloids.
[src:geology/geology] Most research in geology is associated with the study of rocks, as they provide the primary record of the majority of the geological history of the Earth.
[src:geology/geology] There are three major types of rock: igneous, sedimentary, and metamorphic.
[src:geology/geology] The rock cycle illustrates the relationships among them (see diagram).
[src:geology/geology] When a rock solidifies or crystallizes from melt (magma or lava), it is an igneous rock.
[src:geology/geology] The active flow of molten rock is closely studied in volcanology, and igneous petrology aims to determine the history of igneous rocks from their original molten source to their final crystallization.
[src:geology/geology] Rocks can be weathered and eroded, then redeposited and lithified into a sedimentary rock.
[src:geology/geology] Sedimentary rocks are mainly divided into four categories: sandstone, shale, carbonate, and evaporite.
[src:geology/geology] This group of classifications focuses partly on the size of sedimentary particles (sandstone and shale), and partly on mineralogy and formation processes (carbonation and evaporation).
[src:geology/geology] Igneous and sedimentary rocks can then be turned into metamorphic rocks by heat and pressure that change its mineral content, resulting in a characteristic fabric.
[src:geology/geology] All three types may melt again, and when this happens, new magma is formed, from which an igneous rock may once again solidify.
[src:geology/geology] Organic matter, such as coal, bitumen, oil, and natural gas, is linked mainly to organic-rich sedimentary rocks.
[src:geology/geology] To study all three types of rock, geologists evaluate the minerals of which they are composed and their other physical properties, such as texture and fabric.
[src:geology/geology] Geologists study unlithified materials (referred to as *superficial deposits*) that lie above the bedrock.
[src:geology/geology] This study is often known as Quaternary geology, after the Quaternary period of geologic history, which is the most recent period of geologic time.
[src:geology/geology] In the 1960s, it was discovered that the Earth's lithosphere, which includes the crust and rigid uppermost portion of the upper mantle, is separated into tectonic plates that move across the plastically deforming, solid, upper mantle, which is called the asthenosphere.
[src:geology/geology] This theory is supported by several types of observations, including seafloor spreading and the global distribution of mountain terrain and seismicity.
[src:geology/geology] There is an intimate coupling between the movement of the plates on the surface and the convection of the mantle (that is, the heat transfer caused by the slow movement of ductile mantle rock).
[src:geology/geology] Thus, oceanic parts of plates and the adjoining mantle convection currents always move in the same direction – because the oceanic lithosphere is actually the rigid upper thermal boundary layer of the convecting mantle.
[src:geology/geology] This coupling between rigid plates moving on the surface of the Earth and the convecting mantle is called plate tectonics.
[src:geology/geology] The development of plate tectonics has provided a physical basis for many observations of the solid Earth.
[src:geology/geology] Plate tectonics has provided a mechanism for Alfred Wegener's theory of continental drift, in which the continents move across the surface of the Earth over geological time.
[src:geology/geology] They provided a driving force for crustal deformation, and a new setting for the observations of structural geology.
[src:geology/geology] The power of the theory of plate tectonics lies in its ability to combine all of these observations into a single theory of how the lithosphere moves over the convecting mantle, forming a "grand unifying theory of geology".
[src:geology/geology] Advances in seismology, computer modeling, and mineralogy and crystallography at high temperatures and pressures give insights into the internal composition and structure of the Earth.
[src:geology/geology] Seismologists can use the arrival times of seismic waves to image the interior of the Earth.
[src:geology/geology] Early advances in this field showed the existence of a liquid outer core (where shear waves were not able to propagate) and a dense solid inner core.
[src:geology/geology] These advances led to the development of a layered model of the Earth, with a lithosphere (including crust) on top, the mantle below (separated within itself by seismic discontinuities at 410 and 660 kilometers), and the outer core and inner core below that.
[src:geology/geology] Starting in the 1970s, seismologists have been able to use new techniques such as seismic full-waveform inversion to create detailed images of wave speeds inside the earth in the same way a doctor images a body in a CT scan.
[src:geology/geology] These images have led to a much more detailed view of the interior of the Earth, and have replaced the simplified layered model with a much more dynamic model.
[src:geology/geology] Mineralogists have been able to use the pressure and temperature data from the seismic and modeling studies alongside knowledge of the elemental composition of the Earth to reproduce these conditions in experimental settings and measure changes within the crystal structure.
[src:geology/geology] These studies explain the chemical changes associated with the major seismic discontinuities in the mantle and show the crystallographic structures expected in the inner core of the Earth.
[src:geology/geology] The geological time scale encompasses the history of the Earth.
[src:geology/geology] It is bracketed at the earliest by the dates of the first Solar System material at 4.567 Ga (or 4.567 billion years ago) and the formation of the Earth at 4.54 Ga (4.54 billion years), which is the beginning of the Hadean eon – a division of geological time.
[src:geology/geology] At the later end of the scale, it is marked by the present day (in the Holocene epoch).
[src:geology/geology] The following five timelines show the geologic time scale to scale.
[src:geology/geology] The first shows the entire time from the formation of Earth to the present, but this gives little space for the most recent eon.
[src:geology/geology] The second timeline shows an expanded view of the most recent eon.
[src:geology/geology] In a similar way, the most recent era is expanded in the third timeline, the most recent period is expanded in the fourth timeline, and the most recent epoch is expanded in the fifth timeline.
[src:geology/geology] The epochs of lunar history are based on the chronology of impact events, and they are named after defining major impacts.
[src:geology/geology] Hence, the Imbrian is named after the formation of the Mare Imbrium basin.
[src:geology/geology] The ages of older lunar basins can be dated based on the strength of their intrinsic magnetic field, since the early Moon had a magnetic field that faded over time.
[src:geology/geology] The ages of craters can be estimated by morphological and stratigraphic classifications, with younger craters overlapping older impacts and generally showing less impact wear.
[src:geology/geology] Methods for relative dating were developed when geology first emerged as a natural science.
[src:geology/geology] Geologists still use the following principles today as a means to provide information about geological history and the timing of geological events.
[src:geology/geology] The *principle of uniformitarianism* states that the geological processes observed in operation that modify the Earth's crust at present have worked in much the same way over geological time.
[src:geology/geology] The *principle of intrusive relationships* concerns crosscutting intrusions.
[src:geology/geology] In geology, when an igneous intrusion cuts across a formation of sedimentary rock, it can be determined that the igneous intrusion is younger than the sedimentary rock.
[src:geology/geology] Different types of intrusions include stocks, laccoliths, batholiths, sills and dikes.
[src:geology/geology] The *principle of cross-cutting relationships* pertains to the formation of faults and the age of the sequences through which they cut.
[src:geology/geology] Faults are younger than the rocks they cut; accordingly, if a fault is found that penetrates some formations but not those on top of it, then the formations that were cut are older than the fault, and the ones that are not cut must be younger than the fault.
[src:geology/geology] Finding the key bed in these situations may help determine whether the fault is a normal fault or a thrust fault.
[src:geology/geology] The *principle of inclusions and components* states that, with sedimentary rocks, if inclusions (or *clasts*) are found in a formation, then the inclusions must be older than the formation that contains them.
[src:geology/geology] For example, in sedimentary rocks, it is common for gravel from an older formation to be ripped up and included in a newer layer.
[src:geology/geology] A similar situation with igneous rocks occurs when xenoliths are found.
[src:geology/geology] These foreign bodies are picked up as magma or lava flows, and are incorporated, later to cool in the matrix.
[src:geology/geology] As a result, xenoliths are older than the rock that contains them.
[src:geology/geology] The *principle of original horizontality* states that the deposition of sediments occurs as essentially horizontal beds.
[src:geology/geology] Observation of modern marine and non-marine sediments in a wide variety of environments supports this generalization (although cross-bedding is inclined, the overall orientation of cross-bedded units is horizontal).
[src:geology/geology] The *principle of superposition* states that a sedimentary rock layer in a tectonically undisturbed sequence is younger than the one beneath it and older than the one above it.
[src:geology/geology] Logically a younger layer cannot slip beneath a layer previously deposited.
[src:geology/geology] This principle allows sedimentary layers to be viewed as a form of the vertical timeline, a partial or complete record of the time elapsed from deposition of the lowest layer to deposition of the highest bed.
[src:geology/geology] The *principle of faunal succession* is based on the appearance of fossils in sedimentary rocks.
[src:geology/geology] As organisms exist during the same period throughout the world, their presence or (sometimes) absence provides a relative age of the formations where they appear.
[src:geology/geology] Based on principles that William Smith laid out almost a hundred years before the publication of Charles Darwin's theory of evolution, the principles of succession developed independently of evolutionary thought.
[src:geology/geology] The principle becomes quite complex, however, given the uncertainties of fossilization, localization of fossil types due to lateral changes in habitat (facies change in sedimentary strata), and that not all fossils formed globally at the same time.
[src:geology/geology] Geologists use methods to determine the absolute age of rock samples and geological events.
[src:geology/geology] These may be used in conjunction with relative dating methods or to calibrate relative methods.
[src:geology/geology] At the beginning of the 20th century, advancement in geological science was facilitated by the ability to obtain accurate absolute dates to geological events using radioactive isotopes and other methods.
[src:geology/geology] This changed the understanding of geological time.
[src:geology/geology] Previously, geologists could only use fossils and stratigraphic correlation to date sections of rock relative to one another.
[src:geology/geology] With isotopic dates, it became possible to assign absolute ages to rock units, and these absolute dates could be applied to fossil sequences in which there was datable material, converting the old relative ages into new absolute ages.
[src:geology/geology] These are used in geochronologic and thermochronologic studies.
[src:geology/geology] The most suitable isotope systems for this purpose include uranium–lead, rubidium–strontium, and potassium–argon.
[src:geology/geology] Uranium–thorium dating is used for dating calcium-carbonate.
[src:geology/geology] Dating of lava and volcanic ash layers found within a stratigraphic sequence can provide absolute age data for sedimentary rock units that do not contain radioactive isotopes and calibrate relative dating techniques.
[src:geology/geology] These methods can be used to determine ages of pluton emplacement.
[src:geology/geology] Fractionation of the lanthanide series elements is used to compute ages since rocks were removed from the mantle.
[src:geology/geology] Other methods are used for more recent events.
[src:geology/geology] Optically stimulated luminescence and cosmogenic radionuclide dating are used to date surfaces and/or erosion rates.
[src:geology/geology] Dendrochronology can be used for the dating of landscapes.
[src:geology/geology] Radiocarbon dating is used for geologically young materials containing organic carbon.
[src:geology/geology] Thermochemical techniques can be used to determine temperature profiles within the crust, the uplift of mountain ranges, and paleo-topography.
[src:geology/geology] The geology of an area changes through time as rock units are deposited and inserted, and deformational processes alter their shapes and locations.
[src:geology/geology] Rock units are first emplaced either by deposition onto the surface or intrusion into the overlying rock.
[src:geology/geology] Deposition can occur when sediments settle onto the surface of the Earth and later lithify into sedimentary rock, or when as volcanic material such as volcanic ash or lava flows blanket the surface.
[src:geology/geology] Igneous intrusions such as batholiths, laccoliths, dikes, and sills, push upwards into the overlying rock, and crystallize as they intrude.
[src:geology/geology] After the initial sequence of rocks has been deposited, the rock units can be deformed and/or metamorphosed.
[src:geology/geology] Deformation typically occurs as a result of horizontal shortening, horizontal extension, or side-to-side (strike-slip) motion.
[src:geology/geology] These structural regimes broadly relate to convergent boundaries, divergent boundaries, and transform boundaries, respectively, between tectonic plates.
[src:geology/geology] When rock units are placed under horizontal compression, they shorten and become thicker.
[src:geology/geology] Because rock units, other than muds, do not significantly change in volume, this is accomplished in two primary ways: through faulting and folding.
[src:geology/geology] In the shallow crust, where brittle deformation can occur, thrust faults form, which causes the deeper rock to move on top of the shallower rock.
[src:geology/geology] Because deeper rock is often older, as noted by the principle of superposition, this can result in older rocks moving on top of younger ones.
[src:geology/geology] Movement along faults can result in folding, either because the faults are not planar or because rock layers are dragged along, forming drag folds as slip occurs along the fault.
[src:geology/geology] Deeper in the Earth, rocks behave plastically and fold instead of faulting.
[src:geology/geology] These folds can either be those where the material in the center of the fold buckles upwards, creating "antiforms", or where it buckles downwards, creating "synforms".
[src:geology/geology] If the tops of the rock units within the folds remain pointing upwards, they are called anticlines and synclines, respectively.
[src:geology/geology] If some of the units in the fold are facing downward, the structure is called an overturned anticline or syncline, and if all of the rock units are overturned or the correct up-direction is unknown, they are simply called by the most general terms, antiforms, and synforms.
[src:geology/geology] Even higher pressures and temperatures during horizontal shortening can cause both folding and metamorphism of the rocks.
[src:geology/geology] This metamorphism causes changes in the mineral composition of the rocks; creates a foliation, or planar surface, that is related to mineral growth under stress.
[src:geology/geology] This can remove signs of the original textures of the rocks, such as bedding in sedimentary rocks, flow features of lavas, and crystal patterns in crystalline rocks.
[src:geology/geology] Extension causes the rock units as a whole to become longer and thinner.
[src:geology/geology] This is primarily accomplished through normal faulting and through the ductile stretching and thinning.
[src:geology/geology] Normal faults drop rock units that are higher below those that are lower.
[src:geology/geology] This typically results in younger units ending up below older units.
[src:geology/geology] Stretching of units can result in their thinning.
[src:geology/geology] In fact, at one location within the Maria Fold and Thrust Belt, the entire sedimentary sequence of the Grand Canyon appears over a length of less than a meter.
[src:geology/geology] Rocks at the depth to be ductilely stretched are often metamorphosed.
[src:geology/geology] These stretched rocks can pinch into lenses, known as *boudins*, after the French word for "sausage" because of their visual similarity.
[src:geology/geology] Where rock units slide past one another, strike-slip faults develop in shallow regions, and become shear zones at deeper depths where the rocks deform ductilely.
[src:geology/geology] The addition of new rock units, both depositionally and intrusively, often occurs during deformation.
[src:geology/geology] Faulting and other deformational processes result in the creation of topographic gradients, causing material on the rock unit that is increasing in elevation to be eroded by hillslopes and channels.
[src:geology/geology] These sediments are deposited on the rock unit that is going down.
[src:geology/geology] Continual motion along the fault maintains the topographic gradient in spite of the movement of sediment and continues to create accommodation space for the material to deposit.
[src:geology/geology] Deformational events are often associated with volcanism and igneous activity.
[src:geology/geology] Volcanic ashes and lavas accumulate on the surface, and igneous intrusions enter from below.
[src:geology/geology] Dikes, long, planar igneous intrusions, enter along cracks, and therefore often form in large numbers in areas that are being actively deformed.
[src:geology/geology] This can result in the emplacement of dike swarms, such as those that are observable across the Canadian shield, or rings of dikes around the lava tube of a volcano.
[src:geology/geology] All of these processes do not necessarily occur in a single environment and do not necessarily occur in a single order.
[src:geology/geology] The Hawaiian Islands, for example, consist almost entirely of layered basaltic lava flows.
[src:geology/geology] The sedimentary sequences of the mid-continental United States and the Grand Canyon in the southwestern United States contain almost-undeformed stacks of sedimentary rocks that have remained in place since Cambrian time.
[src:geology/geology] Other areas are much more geologically complex.
[src:geology/geology] In the southwestern United States, sedimentary, volcanic, and intrusive rocks have been metamorphosed, faulted, foliated, and folded.
[src:geology/geology] Even older rocks, such as the Acasta gneiss of the Slave craton in northwestern Canada, the oldest known rock in the world have been metamorphosed to the point where their origin is indiscernible without laboratory analysis.
[src:geology/geology] In many places, the Grand Canyon in the southwestern United States being a very visible example, the lower rock units were metamorphosed and deformed, and then deformation ended and the upper, undeformed units were deposited.
[src:geology/geology] Although any amount of rock emplacement and rock deformation can occur, and they can occur any number of times, these concepts provide a guide to understanding the geological history of an area.
[src:geology/geology] Geologists use a number of fields, laboratory, and numerical modeling methods to decipher Earth history and to understand the processes that occur on and inside the Earth.
[src:geology/geology] In typical geological investigations, geologists use primary information related to petrology (the study of rocks), stratigraphy (the study of sedimentary layers), and structural geology (the study of positions of rock units and their deformation).
[src:geology/geology] In many cases, geologists study modern soils, rivers, landscapes, and glaciers; investigate past and current life and biogeochemical pathways, and use geophysical methods to investigate the subsurface.
[src:geology/geology] Sub-specialities of geology may distinguish *endogenous* and *exogenous* geology.
[src:geology/geology] Geological field work varies depending on the task at hand.
[src:geology/geology] , thin sections are used to study rocks.
[src:geology/geology] The method is based on the distinct refractive indexes of different minerals.
[src:geology/geology] In addition to identifying rocks in the field (lithology), petrologists identify rock samples in the laboratory.
[src:geology/geology] Two of the primary methods for identifying rocks in the laboratory are through optical microscopy (such as with the petrographic microscope) and by using an electron microprobe.
[src:geology/geology] In the electron microprobe, individual locations are analyzed for their exact chemical compositions and variation in composition within individual crystals.
[src:geology/geology] Stable and radioactive isotope studies provide insight into the geochemical evolution of rock units.
[src:geology/geology] Petrologists can use fluid inclusion data and perform high temperature and pressure physical experiments to understand the temperatures and pressures at which different mineral phases appear, and how they change through igneous and metamorphic processes.
[src:geology/geology] This research can be extrapolated to the field to understand metamorphic processes and the conditions of crystallization of igneous rocks.
[src:geology/geology] This work can help to explain processes that occur within the Earth, such as subduction and magma chamber evolution.
[src:geology/geology] Structural geologists use microscopic analysis of oriented thin sections of geological samples to observe the fabric within the rocks, which gives information about strain within the crystalline structure of the rocks.
[src:geology/geology] They plot and combine measurements of geological structures to better understand the orientations of faults and folds to reconstruct the history of rock deformation in the area.
[src:geology/geology] In addition, they perform analog and numerical experiments of rock deformation in large and small settings.
[src:geology/geology] The analysis of structures is often accomplished by plotting the orientations of various features onto stereonets.
[src:geology/geology] A stereonet is a stereographic projection of a sphere onto a plane, in which planes are projected as lines and lines are projected as points.
[src:geology/geology] These can be used to find the locations of fold axes, relationships between faults, and relationships between other geological structures.
[src:geology/geology] Among the most well-known experiments in structural geology are those involving orogenic wedges, which are zones in which mountains are built along convergent tectonic plate boundaries.
[src:geology/geology] In the analog versions of these experiments, horizontal layers of sand are pulled along a lower surface into a back stop, which results in realistic-looking patterns of faulting and the growth of a critically tapered (all angles remain the same) orogenic wedge.
[src:geology/geology] Numerical models work in the same way as these analog models, though they are often more sophisticated and can include patterns of erosion and uplift in the mountain belt.
[src:geology/geology] This helps to show the relationship between erosion and the shape of a mountain range.
[src:geology/geology] These studies can give useful information about pathways for metamorphism through pressure, temperature, space, and time.
[src:geology/geology] In the laboratory, stratigraphers analyze samples of stratigraphic sections that can be returned from the field, such as those from drill cores.
[src:geology/geology] Stratigraphers analyze data from geophysical surveys that show the locations of stratigraphic units in the subsurface.
[src:geology/geology] Geophysical data and well logs can be combined to produce a better view of the subsurface, and stratigraphers often use computer programs to do this in three dimensions.
[src:geology/geology] Stratigraphers can then use these data to reconstruct ancient processes occurring on the surface of the Earth, interpret past environments, and locate areas for water, coal, and hydrocarbon extraction.
[src:geology/geology] In the laboratory, biostratigraphers analyze rock samples from outcrop and drill cores for the fossils found in them.
[src:geology/geology] These fossils help scientists to date the core and to understand the depositional environment in which the rock units formed.
[src:geology/geology] Geochronologists precisely date rocks within the stratigraphic section to provide better absolute bounds on the timing and rates of deposition.
[src:geology/geology] Magnetic stratigraphers look for signs of magnetic reversals in igneous rock units within the drill cores.
[src:geology/geology] Other scientists perform stable-isotope studies on the rocks to gain information about past climate.
[src:geology/geology] With the advent of space exploration in the twentieth century, geologists have begun to look at other planetary bodies in the same ways that have been developed to study the Earth.
[src:geology/geology] This new field of study is called planetary geology (sometimes known as astrogeology) and relies on known geological principles to study other bodies of the Solar System.
[src:geology/geology] This is a major aspect of planetary science, and largely focuses on the terrestrial planets, icy moons, asteroids, comets, and meteorites.
[src:geology/geology] However, some planetary geophysicists study the giant planets and exoplanets.
[src:geology/geology] Although the Greek-language-origin prefix *geo* refers to Earth, "geology" is often used in conjunction with the names of other planetary bodies when describing their composition and internal processes: examples are "the geology of Mars" and "Lunar geology".
[src:geology/geology] Specialized terms such as *selenology* (studies of the Moon), *areology* (of Mars), *hermesology* (of Mercury), etc., are also in use.
[src:geology/geology] Although planetary geologists are interested in studying all aspects of other planets, a significant focus is to search for evidence of past or present life on other worlds.
[src:geology/geology] This has led to many missions whose primary or ancillary purpose is to examine planetary bodies for evidence of life.
[src:geology/geology] One of these is the Phoenix lander, which analyzed Martian polar soil for water, chemical, and mineralogical constituents related to biological processes.
[src:geology/geology] Economic geology is a branch of geology that deals with aspects of economic minerals that humankind uses to fulfill various needs.
[src:geology/geology] Economic minerals are those extracted profitably for various practical uses.
[src:geology/geology] Economic geologists help locate and manage the Earth's natural resources, such as petroleum and coal, as well as mineral resources, which include metals such as iron, copper, and uranium.
[src:geology/geology] Mining geology consists of the extractions of mineral and ore resources from the Earth.
[src:geology/geology] Some resources of economic interests include gemstones, metals such as gold and copper, and many industrial minerals such as asbestos, magnesite, perlite, mica, phosphates, zeolites, clay, silica, and pumice, as well as elements such as sulfur and helium.
[src:geology/geology] Petroleum geologists study the locations of the subsurface of the Earth that can contain extractable hydrocarbons, especially petroleum and natural gas.
[src:geology/geology] Because many of these reservoirs are found in sedimentary basins, they study the formation of these basins, their sedimentary and tectonic evolution, and the present-day positions of the rock units.
[src:geology/geology] Engineering geology is the application of geological principles to engineering practice for the purpose of assuring that the geological factors affecting the location, design, construction, operation, and maintenance of engineering works are properly addressed.
[src:geology/geology] Engineering geology is distinct from geological engineering, particularly in North America.
[src:geology/geology] In the field of civil engineering, geological principles and analyses are used in order to ascertain the mechanical principles of the material on which structures are built.
[src:geology/geology] This allows tunnels to be built without collapsing, bridges and skyscrapers to be built with sturdy foundations, and buildings to be built that will not settle in clay and mud.
[src:geology/geology] Geology and geological principles can be applied to various environmental problems such as stream restoration, the restoration of brownfields, and the understanding of the interaction between natural habitat and the geological environment.
[src:geology/geology] Groundwater hydrology, or hydrogeology, is used to locate groundwater, which can often provide a ready supply of uncontaminated water and is especially important in arid regions, and to monitor the spread of contaminants in groundwater wells.
[src:geology/geology] Geologists obtain data through stratigraphy, boreholes, core samples, and ice cores.
[src:geology/geology] Ice cores and sediment cores are used for paleoclimate reconstructions, which tell geologists about past and present temperature, precipitation, and sea level across the globe.
[src:geology/geology] These datasets are our primary source of information on global climate change outside of instrumental data.
[src:geology/geology] Geologists and geophysicists study natural hazards in order to enact safe building codes and warning systems that are used to prevent loss of property and life.
[src:geology/geology] The study of the physical material of the Earth dates back at least to ancient Greece when Theophrastus (372–287 BCE) wrote the work *Peri Lithon* (*On Stones*).
[src:geology/geology] During the Roman period, Pliny the Elder wrote in detail of the many minerals and metals, then in practical use – even correctly noting the origin of amber.
[src:geology/geology] Additionally, in the 4th century BCE Aristotle made critical observations of the slow rate of geological change.
[src:geology/geology] He observed the composition of the land and formulated a theory where the Earth changes at a slow rate and that these changes cannot be observed during one person's lifetime.
[src:geology/geology] Aristotle developed one of the first evidence-based concepts connected to the geological realm regarding the rate at which the Earth physically changes.
[src:geology/geology] Abu al-Rayhan al-Biruni (973–1048 CE) was one of the earliest Persian geologists, whose works included the earliest writings on the geology of India, hypothesizing that the Indian subcontinent was once a sea.
[src:geology/geology] Georgius Agricola (1494–1555) published his groundbreaking work *De Natura Fossilium* in 1546 and is seen as the founder of geology as a scientific discipline.
[src:geology/geology] Nicolas Steno (1638–1686) is credited with the law of superposition, the principle of original horizontality, and the principle of lateral continuity: three defining principles of stratigraphy.
[src:geology/geology] The word *geology* was first used by Ulisse Aldrovandi in 1603, then by Jean-André Deluc in 1778 and introduced as a fixed term by Horace-Bénédict de Saussure in 1779.
[src:geology/geology] The word is derived from the Greek γῆ, *gê*, meaning "earth" and λόγος, *logos*, meaning "speech".
[src:geology/geology] But according to another source, the word "geology" comes from a Norwegian, Mikkel Pedersøn Escholt (1600–1669), who was a priest and scholar.
[src:geology/geology] Escholt first used the definition in his book titled, *Geologia Norvegica* (1657).
[src:geology/geology] William Smith (1769–1839) drew some of the first geological maps and began the process of ordering rock strata (layers) by examining the fossils contained in them.
[src:geology/geology] In 1763, Mikhail Lomonosov published his treatise *On the Strata of Earth*.
[src:geology/geology] His work was the first narrative of modern geology, based on the unity of processes in time and explanation of the Earth's past from the present.
[src:geology/geology] James Hutton (1726–1797) is often viewed as the first modern geologist.
[src:geology/geology] In 1785 he presented a paper entitled *Theory of the Earth* to the Royal Society of Edinburgh.
[src:geology/geology] In his paper, he explained his theory that the Earth must be much older than had previously been supposed to allow enough time for mountains to be eroded and for sediments to form new rocks at the bottom of the sea, which in turn were raised up to become dry land.
[src:geology/geology] Hutton published a two-volume version of his ideas in 1795.
[src:geology/geology] The first geological map of the U.S. was produced in 1809 by William Maclure.
[src:geology/geology] In 1807, Maclure commenced the self-imposed task of making a geological survey of the United States.
[src:geology/geology] Almost every state in the Union was traversed and mapped by him, the Allegheny Mountains being crossed and recrossed some 50 times.
[src:geology/geology] The results of his unaided labours were submitted to the American Philosophical Society in a memoir entitled *Observations on the Geology of the United States explanatory of a Geological Map*, and published in the *Society's Transactions*, together with the nation's first geological map.
[src:geology/geology] This antedates William Smith's geological map of England by six years, although it was constructed using a different classification of rocks.
[src:geology/geology] Sir Charles Lyell (1797–1875) first published his famous book, *Principles of Geology*, in 1830.
[src:geology/geology] This book, which influenced the thought of Charles Darwin, successfully promoted the doctrine of uniformitarianism.
[src:geology/geology] This theory states that slow geological processes have occurred throughout the Earth's history and are still occurring today.
[src:geology/geology] In contrast, catastrophism is the theory that Earth's features formed in single, catastrophic events and remained unchanged thereafter.
[src:geology/geology] Though Hutton believed in uniformitarianism, the idea was not widely accepted at the time.
[src:geology/geology] Much of 19th-century geology revolved around the question of the Earth's exact age.
[src:geology/geology] Estimates varied from a few hundred thousand to billions of years.
[src:geology/geology] By the early 20th century, radiometric dating allowed the Earth's age to be estimated at two billion years.
[src:geology/geology] The awareness of this vast amount of time opened the door to new theories about the processes that shaped the planet.
[src:geology/geology] Some of the most significant advances in 20th-century geology have been the development of the theory of plate tectonics in the 1960s and the refinement of estimates of the planet's age.
[src:geology/geology] Plate tectonics theory arose from two separate geological observations: seafloor spreading and continental drift.
[src:geology/geology] The theory revolutionized the Earth sciences.
[src:geology/geology] Today the Earth is known to be approximately 4.5 billion years old.
[src:geology/logy] Philology is an exception: while its meaning is closer to the first sense, the etymology of the word is similar to the second sense.
[src:geology/logy] In English names for fields of study, the suffix *-logy* is most frequently found preceded by the euphonic connective vowel *o* so that the word ends in *-ology*.
[src:geology/logy] In these Greek words, the root is always a noun and *-o-* is the combining vowel for all declensions of Greek nouns.
[src:geology/logy] Linguists sometimes jokingly refer to haplology as *haplogy* (subjecting the word *haplology* to the process of haplology itself).
[src:geology/logy] Per metonymy, words ending in *-logy* are sometimes used to describe a subject rather than the study of it (e.g., *technology*).
[src:geology/logy] This usage is particularly widespread in medicine; for example, *pathology* is often used simply to refer to "the disease" itself (e.g., "We haven't found the pathology yet") rather than "the study of a disease".
[src:geology/logy] Books, journals, and treatises about a subject also often bear the name of this subject (e.g., the scientific journal *Ecology*).
[src:geology/logy] When appended to other English words, the suffix can also be used humorously to create nonce words (e.g., *beerology* as "the study of beer").
[src:geology/logy] As with other classical compounds, adding the suffix to an initial word-stem derived from Greek or Latin may be used to lend grandeur or the impression of scientific rigor to humble pursuits, as in *cosmetology* ("the study of beauty treatment") or *cynology* ("the study of dog training").
[src:geology/logy] The -logy or -ology suffix is commonly used to indicate finite series of art works like books or movies.
[src:geology/logy] For paintings, the "tych" suffix is more common (e.g. diptych, triptych).
[src:geology/logy] Further terms like duology (two, mostly in genre fiction) quadrilogy (four) and octalogy (eight) have been coined but are rarely used: for a series of 10, sometimes "decalog" is used (e.g. in the Virgin Decalog) instead of "decalogy".
